text.description1: Vaggiri is a great dive site for every diver, especially those who love to see small life and have long dives. The formation of this giri is very unique and a perfect place to try out deep dives for the first time.
text.description2: Anemone fishes, groupers, frogfish, ghost pipe fish, school of bat fishes, stonefish, and scorpionfish.

text.description1: The third channel to the west of Fulidhoo offers a great dive to see big fish during incoming currents at both channel entrances. The south side has larger overhangs and cavities starting at 10m down to 30m+ moving further into the channel. Along the reef edge you will mostly find grey reef- and white-tip sharks.
text.description2: Generally more life on the south of the channel which also features more soft and hard coral than the north side. Larger schools of fish, eg. bluefin trevally, might surround you.

text.description1: The back reef of Fulidhoo extends over roughly 4km from west to east. The central part features a sloping reef with magnificent table corals on the top and wide overhangs from a depth of 15m to beyond 30m. The area between the caves and top reef is full of marine life.
text.description2: The reef hosts an abundance of small reef fish, moray eels, humphead wrasses, batfishes, reef sharks, rays and many more.

text.description1: A small Giri with an abundance of corals, reef life and names, eg. Floral Garden, Teabag-Giri or Aquarium. The top of the reef starts at 1m at low tide and extends down to 20m+ on certain parts of the seamount. Most of the days you will be able to go around the whole circular reef as the currents are small.
text.description2: High chance to dive with various schools of fish, like blue-lined or humpback snappers, yellowtop fusiliers, trevallies or sergeant majors.

text.description1: South west corner of Rihiveli island. This divesite at the corner of the wide channel is a perfect place to observe grey reef sharks. Can be dived with outgoing and incoming current. Offers beautiful overhangs teaming with life.
text.description2: Frequently seen marine life: grey reef sharks, eagle rays, lobsters, tunas, giant trevallies, schools of fish, moray eels, octopus...

text.description1: Rani Corner is a beautiful inner reef dive with a wall starting at around 5 meters and gradually slopping down till 30 meters, with lots of overhangs in between 10-25 meters with great hard and soft corals.
text.description2: Frequently Seen: Napoleon wrasse, Whitetip reef shark, Moray Eel, Fish Schools, Hawksbill Turtles, and, with luck, Ribbon Eels.

text.description1: Beautiful inner reef dive with lots of overhangs between 10 and 25 meters. Great hard on the reef and nice colorful soft corals in the overhangs. Torch highly recommended!
text.description2: Frequently seen marine life: Napoleons, white tip reef sharks, fish schools, turtles, shells, moray eels, lobster, halimeda ghost pipe fish...

text.description1: Manta Rays cleaning station. Great amount of mantas spotted here during outgoing currents between May and December. Maximum depth is 18 meters. Possible strong currents, when this happens, visibility tends to be poor, around 10 meters.
text.description2: Reef Manta rays, white tip reef sharks, sweet lips, yellow snapers, red snappers and lots of small fauna.

text.description1: The Rihiveli wreck is a 45 meters long steel freighter with interesting marine life around. The visibility is mostly not the best, but there are chances to see manta rays there.
text.description2: Frequently seen: big pufferfish, groupers, bluefin trevallies, sweetlips, manta rays, stingrays, nurse sharks.

text.description1: Just off the end of the main island reef, this thila sits on the edge of the atoll just in the channel. As such, it gets good pelagics when the current runs like whitetip reef sharks, and occasional manta and hammerheads. Come up on the deep side to check out the frequent eagle rays found cruising this dive site.
text.description2: The ledges on the seaward side have hard corals and plenty of reef life. You might see napoleon wrasse, sea turtles, or pompano here.

text.description1: Farukolhu Kandu (Fulidhoo Channel), a short boat ride from Fulidhoo, is a drift dive for all levels of divers. The reef is situated on a shallow channel, between 8 to 30 m.
text.description2: You can find a large variety of marine life, from the smallest nudibranch or blenny all the way to eagle-rays and sharks.

text.description1: There is a coral block in 19 Meters of depth, still beautiful and untouched, with all kind of corals. and surrounded by sand. There are a lot of cleaner wrasses around, so the reef mantas come in to get cleaned. Divers can sit on the sand and watch the mantas coming in and out, without harming corals.
text.description2: Avoid getting too close to the cleaning station or swim around, otherwise the manta rays will disappear. Apart from the manta rays, all kind of coral fishes, stingrays and eagle rays.

text.description1: The outside of this long and narrow thila is covered of hard corals and offers a great variety of marine life. Dolphins are often spotted playing in this area.
text.description2: Frequently seen marine life: nurse sharks, turtles, stingrays, lionfish, sweelips, schools of fish, dolphins.

text.description1: Fihalhohi Beru is a beautiful thila on the outside reef. There are many schools of fish and often big fish if there is some current. Around the overhangs on the west side you might encounter nurse sharks. Taking a torch is recommended.
text.description2: Frequently spotted: Napoleon wrasse, Stingrays closer to reef or at the bottom, Turtles, Scorpionfish, Nudibranches.

text.description1: Huge schools of yellow back and neon fusiliers swarm around the thila together with schools of trevally and barracuda are also around, ready to hunt and feast on the smaller fish.
text.description2: Schools of big eye travely, Napoleon Wrasse, lots of Morey eels and Lionfish. Eagle rays, white tip reef sharks, and nurse sharks are also seen.

text.description1: Very nice landscape with beautiful coral rock formations between 5 and 20 meters. In between the rock formations are sandy plateaus with leather and soft corals. Torch and camera recommended.
text.description2: Frequently seen: whitetip reefsharks, schools of sweetlips, garden eels, moray eels, stingray, schools of fusilliers.

text.description1: At the outside reef of Fihalohi, a gentle slope goes down to 20 meters. In the sandy bottom there are stone corals and, within it, shelter loads of glassfish and cleaning shrimps.
text.description2: Frequently Seen: Whitetip reef sharks and stingrays on the sandy bottom, turtles, and eagle rays cruising in the shallower reef.

text.description1: Easy dive along the inside reef and around a thila. If the current allows it, it is also very nice to dive the small thila on the north west side.
text.description2: Frequently seen sealife: stingrays, hawksbill turtles, dogtooth tunas, garden eels, moray eels, snappers...

text.description1: Five minutes away from Rihiveli Resort, located on north east side of Rihiveli. bay is formed from five meters going down to 12 meters, for beginners those who love to do free diving.
text.description2: Five minutes away from Rihiveli Resort, located on north east side of Rihiveli. bay is formed from five meters going down to 12 meters, for beginners those who love to do free diving.

text.description1: Easy dive on the outside reef wall with a lot of sea life to see and find until a depth of 20 meters. Beautiful overhangs between 8 to 18 meters. Very nice for underwater photography. Torch is highly recommended.
text.description2: Frequently seen sea life: Turtles, Reef sharks, Napoleon wrasse, Lionfish, Nudibranchs, Octopus, Halimeda ghost pipefish, Dogtooth tuna... and a lot of colorful fish!

text.description1: This is an outside reef generally dived on the westside with a lot of small stone corals. In between the north and south reef, there is a small Thila. It is quite exciting to cross the small channels.
text.description2: At the Thila itself, depending on the currents, we can get quite lucky with some cruising Grey reef sharks, Whitetip reef sharks, and eagle rays passing by.

text.description1: Outside reef with an interesting “entrance“ into the channel. Big blocks at 20 meters as well as hard corals. Great variety of marine life. Torch highly recommended.
text.description2: Frequently seen marine life: whitetip reefsharks, hawksbill turtles, dolphins, eagle rays, napoleonwrasses, schools of bannerfish.

text.description1: Protected bay area with beautiful reef, white sandy patches and coral structures for every level. From beginners to advanced divers, perfect for an easy enjoyable dive.
text.description2: Healthy reef with clouds of small coral fish. Frequently seen: marbled ray, hawksbill turtles, midnight snappers school, lots of reef fish.

text.description1: Two Thilas inside the atoll with many nice overhangs at the north and south east corner between 10 and 20 meters. Many coral blocks and sponges. Torch recommended
text.description2: Frequently seen: lobsters, stingrays, glassfish, ghost pipefish, withe tip sharks, turtle, schooling fish, moray eels.

text.description1: This is a small inside reef with a drop off on the west side. This site is full of holes and overhangs in between 5 - 12 meters. Sponges and black coral are abundant. Diving with a torch is highly recommended.
text.description2: Frequently seen: Hawksbill Turtles, Nudibranchs, schools of Fusiliers, Moray eels, Clown fish, and Blue fin trevallys in action passing by.

text.description1: This is a small inside reef, with a drop off on the west side and lots of overhangs. A torch is recommended. This site is full of hard corals on the top reef and is one of the best sites known for its coral.
text.description2: Frequently Seen: Octopus, Turtles, Scorpionfish, and schooling fusiliers that are hunted by Blue fin trevallys or Tunas, and lots of snappers.

text.description1: This is a very good dive site for all kinds of divers, starting with a gentle slope in the sandy bottom and then moving on to the reef which is quite widespread, with a maximum depth of 17 meters. Since its also a nursery for juveniles, some trevallys coming in to feed.
text.description2: Lots of colorful reef fish which include, Sweetlips, Emperors, Mackerels, and schools of fusiliers. With a bit of luck you can come across Rays, Turtles, and Whitetip reef sharks.

text.description1: Rannalhi Jetty lies on the Northern Tip of Rannalhi Island - easiest entry point would be from the beach itself. The underwater topography offers a maximum depth of 25 meters, the reef structure creates various reef potholes with a sandy bottom, surrounded by coral blocks and several smaller Giris to dive around.
text.description2: Many nursesharks, black- and whitetip sharks, also sting- and eagle rays and a big variety of fish. Many sea sponges in different sizes growing along the seabed, many hard coral blocks.

text.description1: Admiral 3 is on the North side of Rannalhi on the outside reef in the channel. It is a wall that starts at 7 meters, and the drop-off continues down to 28 meters. There is a good chance to see big fish in the channel entry.
text.description2: With a bit of luck we can spot nurse sharks in the bomie of the south-east lagoon, or at the east cave. White-tip reef sharks and stingrays are found on the sandy bottom, and eagle rays cruise by.

text.description1: Long inside reef with different coral blocks and sandy areas. Many table corals and hard coral formations with a depth varying between 2 to 24 meters.
text.description2: Frequently seen sea life: Nursesharks, Moray eels, Turtles, Nudibranches, Lobsters, Schooling fish, White tip sharks...

text.description1: Drop off located at the corner and at the outside reef with a lot of small and very big overhangs form 5 meters to 20 meters. Whip corals inside the channel and many anemones.
text.description2: Frequently seen marine life: Napoleon, Jackfish, schools of fish, Cowries, Moray eels, Sweetlips, Nudibranches, White tip sharks, Halimeda ghost pipefish.

text.description1: Small round reef with a deeper thila attached to the north west side of the giri. The deeper thila has some big black corals with longnose hawkfish and a big scool of five line snappers. The west side offers a nice dropping slope with nice small overhangs. Torch recommended.
text.description2: Frequently seen: turtles, octopus, scorpionfish, trevallies, nudibranches, big school of five line snappers, longnose hawkfish, moray eels.

text.description1: This dive site is quite unique in the fact that the pinnacle has split into five pieces over thousands of years of erosion. The pieces of pinnacle lay at depths of between 12m and 40m.
text.description2: This dive site is great for beautiful vibrant coral life as well as schools of sweetlips, macro life such as frogfish and stingrays / white tip reef sharks.

text.description1: Small Giri with beautiful coral blocks on the west side. This giri is covered with fields of anemones and different types of anemone fish. Easy dive.
text.description2: Frequently seen marine life: schooling fish, hawksbill turtles, white tip sharks, octopus, scorpionfish, nudibranchs

text.description1: Mid sized Giri with lots of beautiful soft corals on the south and east side. Various sandy areas with blocks and nice table corals. Ideal place for snorkelers too.
text.description2: Frequently seen: turtles, schooling fishes, sweetlips, scorpionfishes, nudibranches, fusiliers, moray eels, shrimps.

text.description1: Dongmas Giri is a small round reef in the middle of the atoll. A drop off from 1-12 meters on the south side is where there are small bomies covered with compact coral that shelter loads of glass fish. The west side has some beautiful overhangs. Diving with a torch is highly recommended.
text.description2: Frequently seen: Turtles, Octopus, Nudibranchs, Big Groupers, Pipe fish on the south side, Black corals, and schools of yellow back fusilier.

text.description1: Appa Thila is a large reef on the inside of the atoll. West side of the reef is a beautiful terrace with lots of soft corals. In 60 minutes it is possible to swim around half of the site. Small overhangs can be seen on the east side. A great dive site for photographers.
text.description2: Frequently seen: Octopus and schools of fusilier. With a bit of luck you will see white tip reef sharks, hawksbill turtles, and marbled stingrays.

text.description1: This is a small reef situated inside the atoll with a drop-off on the west side. The reef is full of holes and overhangs, with sponges and black corals. A torch and camera are highly recommended.
text.description2: Frequently seen: Octopus, Hawksbill Turtles, schooling fish, a lot of macro stuff like Nudibranchs and Flatworms.

text.description1: This outside reef is also called “Balcony“ and features big fish. The landscape is beautiful with a lot of small overhangs at 20 meters. Torches are recommended. This site is generally dived in an east - west current.
text.description2: With a bit of luck you will come across Eagle rays, White tip reef sharks, and Stingrays resting by the sandy bottom, plus Turtles and Napoleons towards the top reef.

text.description1: The dive school located at the end of the main jetty offers access to the house reef, giving you easy excess to the seamless drop-off for diving and snorkeling. One of the best house reef resorts in the Maldives. Night feeding manta rays are here almost every night.
text.description2: Manta Rays, school of eagle rays, green turtle and hawksbil turtle, Giant travely , tunas jack fishes, frog fish.

text.description1: A stunning underwater pinnacle just minutes away from the island of Kuda Rah. This dive site has been declared a protected marine area. The dive site is better for Advanced certified divers and those who are experienced with a bit of current. Nitrox is recommended.
text.description2: Large schools of bluestripe snapper hang out on the top of this thila, creating a sea of yellow and blue, schools of fusilier, and batfish are also nearby. Possibilities of grey reef sharks

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: When the current starts coming in from the west side of the atoll, you better not miss this spectacular dive site! It is a pinnacle a thila but very large with a shallow top reef. This dive site has one of the best fish life combinations from very tiny to very large.
text.description2: Grey reef sharks, white tip reef sharks, nurse sharks, eagle rays, turtles and tiger sharks.

text.description1: Beautiful channel dive with the option to dive the outside reef. Very nice coral blocks surrounded by sandy areas inside the channel. Depth between 5 to 20 meters. Torch and camera recommended.
text.description2: Frequently seen marine life: mobula rays, reef fish, napoleons, turtles, schools of fish, sharks, eagle rays...

text.description1: Easy dive site on the outside reef. The drop off (wall) sets back to a large cavity in the reef. Beautiful coral blocks are covered with soft corals. Many species of reef fish are around found the rocks. The drop off changes to a sandy area at 20 to 25 meters. Bring your torch and camera!
text.description2: Frequently seen marine life: sharks, napoleons, moray eels, sweetlips, eagle rays, trevallies, turtles, halimeda ghost pipe fish, nudibranchs, lionfish...

text.description1: This channel site is in the northeast of Vaavu atoll. This site is more suited to advanced divers as you can encounter strong currents. When there is less current, the dive site can also be for less experienced divers.
text.description2: Miyaru Kandu - “Shark Channel“ gets its name from the sharks that can be spotted in the middle of the channel.

text.description1: Small thila in the Vaageli channel. You can dive around it within one hour. The thila has many blocks and nice terraces. The top of the thila is at 10 meters.
text.description2: Frequently seen marine life: white tip sharks, eagle rays, octopus, flatworms, lionfish, schooling fish, nudibranchs, shrimps.

text.description1: This is a good drift dive in the channel of Vaagali. The reef starts at 5 meters and drops down to the sandy bottom to 28 meters. Lots of overhangs are found in between 10-20 meters with black corals and soft corals. A dive light is highly recommended.
text.description2: Frequently Seen: Whitetip reef sharks, Grey reef sharks, Stingrays, Eagle rays, Napoleon wrasse, and Turtles.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: This dive is located on the west side of this atoll with plenty of colorful fish life and amazing features of overhangs. The formations of this reef and channel are the territory of napoleon wrasse and groupers, along with barracudas.
text.description2: You will see eagle rays, tunas, blue fin jacks, and trevallies, black snappers, white tip reef sharks and nurse sharks. School of banner fish are all over the top reef.

text.description1: Outer reef diving site on the local island of Dhighura - reef slowly sloping down from 0 to approx. 10 m, then more or less steep wall up to over 40 m with smaller overhangs. Depending on the current, right or left shoulder along the reef.
text.description2: Well-known diving site for whale sharks, lots of boat traffic looking for the sharks. Various fish schools along the reef and in the open water. SMB Highly recommended.

text.description1: Kalhu Thila is situated right in the center of the atoll and is a small pinnacle with lots of soft corals and overhangs. This is the perfect site to do your night dive. The pinnacle starts from 3 meters and drops down to 28 meters.
text.description2: During night dives you can frequently spot colorful Feather stars, Flatworms, Nudibranchs, lots of different kind of shrimps and crabs, and Lionfish in action.

text.description1: Ran Thila is an underwater knoll, with a gentle slope on the north-east and East side and a drop off on the west side with a lot of overhangs and caves in between 5-20 meters. A torch is recommended.
text.description2: Lots of colorful soft corals in the overhangs and caves. This is a very good dive site to spot macro stuff like Nudibranchs or flatworms. With a bit of luck you can come across Frogfish.

text.description1: This medium-sized steel wreck was sunk on purpose in 1998, this was to provide the many divers visiting South Ari Atoll with a wreck dive site. This site is very close to the house reef of Machafushi island.
text.description2: A great site for macro lovers as you will find many species of nudibranch, shrimp, and crabs around the wreck, quite often there is a frogfish hiding on the wreck if you can spot him!

text.description1: This dive site is in the channel of Lohifushi, with a sandy bottom between 15 - 25 meters. You can dive both sides of the 50-meter large sand channel. In the sand, you can find many coral blocks.
text.description2: Frequently seen: White tip reef sharks, Turtles, Shells, Sweetlips, Bannerfish, schooling fish, Nudibranchs, and, depending on the currents, Manta rays.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: This is a long, gently dropping reef. An easy dive site for every level of diver. Best depth is in the 5 to 20-meter zone. During the month of August, there is a strong possibility to see whale sharks with the small incoming south to east current.
text.description2: Honeycomb moray eels, green turtles, and red tooth triggerfish are all over the place. Also, oriental sweetlips, hump heads, red snappers, and school of fusiliers.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: Locally, Mendhu Ingili means “middle finger.“ This dive site is a hidden treasure with a beautiful reef away from the busy and famous Guraidhoo corner. Diversity is rich here due to the flow of nutritious ocean currents.
text.description2: You will see eagle rays, whitetip reef sharks, lots of small fish life, oriental sweet lips, leaf fish, ghost pipefish, and giant moray eels.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: This dive site is well known as a Manta Ray Cleaning and feeding zone from late March to begining of November and some times into mid-December. This is one of the best places to dive with these giant rays within this part of the Atoll.
text.description2: Manta rays, stingrays, occasional nurse sharks, leopard sharks, and whale sharks have been spotted at this dive site during the month of August.

text.description1: This dive site is located on east side of dive point rannalhi, boat navigation time is 40min. Its a very small round giri, you can swim around in one hour.
text.description2: This Giri is a rocky environment with a lot of black sponges, corals, and many fishes, including: Napoleon, Tuna, Turtles for example.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll
SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: One of the interesting attractions during the northeast monsoon, this site offers a wide variety of big fish life. The entire channel is a marine protected area. Be well prepared for several downstream washing machine currents when drifting to the inside channel.
text.description2: Grey reef sharks,eagle rays, turtles, barracudas, occasional visits by whale sharks and black mantas.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: Middle point “MEDHU FARU“ offers different varieties of fish life. At 30m overhangs are covered with sea fans and between 8-20m. Drifting to the inside will take you along rich coral formations. The best diving can be archived during a north east current.
text.description2: You will see jack fish, groupers, napoleon wrasse, red snappers, white tip reef sharks, turtles, moray eels, and dog tooth tunas.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: Kuda Kandu means small channel and is situated north of Guraidhoo channel, which has a very shallow sandy bottom at 12 meters deep and 10 meters wide. It is deep inside the atoll with colonies of stony corals which give good hide away spots to blue stripe yellow snappers.
text.description2: You will see white tip reef sharks, green turtlse, napoleon wrasses, Jack fishes, Ribbon eels, and grey reef sharks.

text.description1: Lhosfushi corner can be dived with strong or medium flowing inward or outward of the atoll, or with no current at all. It’s therefore a suitable dive site for all level, with both good hard & soft corals, and a very dense fish life.
text.description2: All types of common reef fishes in abundance, turtles, macro, white tips sharks, napoleon wrasse, mantas during the season.

text.description1: Beautiful outside reef dive. Many big and small coral blocks between 5-15 meters. A gentle drop off going down to 30 meters. Best to be dived in an East to West current.
text.description2: Frequently seen: White tip reef sharks, Green sea Turtle, Long fin Banner fish, cruising Eagle rays, Napoleon Wrasse.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: This dive site is named Napoleon Reef for good reason. This site is covered in large Napolean wrasses. This is a good drift dive for all levels of diver. Many times divers have also encountered whale sharks and mobula rays here as well.
text.description2: You will see napoleon wrasses, mobula rays, green and hawksbill sea turtles, white-tip reef sharks, and manta rays passing by during the month of August.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll
SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: Kandooma Caves is blissful with huge green sea turtles. Most divers average seeing 8-9 turtles in a single dive. You will drift along at an average depth of 25 meters where you will see large coral blocks surrounded by Oriental sweet lips and emperors.
text.description2: You will see green sea turtles, grey reef sharks, eagle and mobula rays, barracuda, nurse sharks, lobsters, giant trevally, and dogtooth tunas.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll
SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: With a slow incoming current Kandoo Kan is a great site of beginner divers to observe plenty of big fish life close to the reef. This is one of the best dive sites to encounter huge green sea turtles.
text.description2: You will see green sea turtles, grey reef sharks, white tip reef sharks, stingrays, and eagle rays. There are also schools of red snappers and oriental sweet lips.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll
SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll
SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: This “Thila” is in the middle of the kandooma kandu. From 2000 to 2009 this dive site was ranked world 10th place of shark diving. The top of the reef is full of hard corals. The sides of the “Thila” are covered with soft corals. The currents are strong here and highly recommend for Advanced and Nitrox divers.
text.description2: The many species to discover and encounter which include big schools of eagle rays, white tip sharks, barracudas green turtles and grey reef sharks, Tiger shark as a guest appearance

text.description1: Your best dive at Cocoa Corner will be when the northeast incoming ocean current hits this atoll, which then only requires you a minimal fin kick to cruise along. This can be a long drift or a short drift dive. Make sure you do not miss the corner.
text.description2: White tip and grey reef sharks, hawksbill and huge green turtles, tunas and which luck a surprise appearance of thresher sharks, leatherback turtles, marlins and hammerheads.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: Are you looking for a long drift dive? This dive site is 20-35 minutes away from dive centers. Mostly green sea turtles are on top of the reef awaiting the cleaner wrasses and for your camera.
text.description2: Honeycomb moray eels, green & hawksbill turtles, white tip reef sharks, dog tooth tunas, octopuses, plenty of fusiliers all over the place.

text.description1: Named after the nearby sandbank were “scantily clad“ tourists from Maafushi used to come to frolic before the opening of Bikini Beach on the island. Nice dive site for macro & night dives, with healthy coral and good fish life. Turtles are present, along with Mobula rays and the occasional white tip reef shark.
text.description2: You will see octopus, frogfish, lionfish, scorpionfish, midnight snappers, hawksbill sea turtles, Mobula rays, garden eels, nudibranchs, and more!

text.description1: Underwater seamount- called Thila in Maldives, top reef at 7-10 meters. Negative decent needed away from the reef if there is current. High concentration of fish on the current side. Lots of schooling fishes, Tunas and big stuff such as sharks and rays. Beautiful cracks and holes with all kind of surprises.
text.description2: Redtooth triggerfishes, fuesiliers, groupers, sharks , hawksbill turtles, all kind of scorpion fishes and many anemones with clownfishes. Lots of re-growing stone corals.

text.description1: Fish Head Thila was formerly known for its enormous population of grey reef sharks. Now it depends on luck, season and the current to see them. The reef plate starts at about 10 meters depth and there can be currents. Fast descent required.
text.description2: More current, more fish! Big schools of Fusiliers, blue striped snappers, morays, tunas, jacks, whitetip and grey reef sharks

text.description1: Named after a customer participating in a “search for new dive site“, Yaara giri is an easy dive site, with an interesting topography (wall, sand slopes, reef outcrops), decent corals and a good fish life. Occasional hawksbill turtles and white tip reef sharks can be seen here, on top of the usual reef fish.
text.description2: School of banner fish, groupers, giant moray, groupers, octopus, nudibranchs, dog tooth tunas, hawksbill turtles, scorpion fish

text.description1: This is a shore dive, 2 to 3m deep, approximately 200m in length, has a sandy bottom with patches of seaweed, coral blocks, and is part of the Maldives Passions Coral Growing Farm Project.
text.description2: Many types of juvenile reef fish, some crustaceans & shells, juvenile  blacktip sharks, juvenile stingray, adult eagle rays, and occasional hawksbill turtles.

text.description1: Small caves & overhangs that lays in the middle of the pass between Maafushi & Anantara Resort. Good fish life, and nice soft coral growing underneath the coral formations, tucked away from light and current, which can be quite strong here.
text.description2: All type of reef fish, some macro (nudibranches), garden eels in the sandy area, jackfish, and the occasional turtle.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: The Kuda Giri is a very pretty, old wreck accessible by short swim from the pinnacle. This is a boat dive with an excellent, small wreck sitting next to a very well established giri (pinnacle) with lots of small caves and overhangs.
text.description2: The outside of the ship is covered with corals, algae, sponges, colorful sea squirts, and little fish with the odd grey frogfish found on the deck.

text.description1: Dive site right on the corner of Maamigili Island at the southern end of the Ari Atoll, which also has an airport. Outer reef slowly sloping down to approx. 10 m, then more or less steep wall up to over 40 meters with smaller overhangs and crevices. Depending on the current, right or left shoulder along the reef.
text.description2: Best-known diving spot for whale sharks, lots of schooling fish along the edge of the reef. Be careful when surfacing as there is often heavy boat traffic. SMB highly recommended.

text.description1: Lumboa Giri is located quite close to Kuda Giri, and it’s a quite similar dive site, although smaller and without the wreck. A nice pinnacle, with an interesting configuration, it boasts with nice hard & soft corals, a good fish life, and makes for an interesting macro option.
text.description2: Small reef fishes, macro, octopus, occasional hawksbill turtle, dogtooth tunas, bluefin trevallies, garden eels, swim-through & overhangs.

text.description1: Small beautiful Thila, reef top 10-12 meter deep. Negative decent needed. You can swim around if the current is not too strong several times. Overhangs gives you protection from current and to watch fish life.
text.description2: Especially in current lots of fish life, fuesiliers, surgeant fishes, tunas, jack fishes. Whitetip reef sharks and eagle rays are frequently visitors. Black coral with hawkfishes...

text.description1: This wreck site requires a short swim from the nearby reef “Kuda Giri“ to reach it. This well-preserved wreck sunk in 1994 and is teaming with marine life. The wreck top is located at around 20m, and the propeller is located around 33m. Torch highly recommended as the colors will prove to be vibrant with light.
text.description2: Frequently seen marine life: nudibranchs, moray eels, lionfish, groupers, snappers, trevallies and octopus

text.description1: Dhigu Thila lies in the pass between the local island of Gulhi & the resort of Anantara. A quite long thila, it boasts majestic sea fans, beautiful soft & hard corals, and a dense & thriving fish life. Marble sting rays, eagle rays, grey reef sharks, occasional manta rays, and good macro is what you can expect here.
text.description2: Bump head parrotfish, white tip sharks, green & hawksbill turtles, napoleon wrasse, schools of red snappers & blue lined snappers, oriental & giant sweetlips, gorgonians, nurse sharks.

text.description1: Mas Thila means as much as fish mountain. One thing is for sure - the name is program! Starting from its topreef at 8 meters the reef goes down far beyond 30 meters at some places...
text.description2: Sensational amount of fussiliers and surgeonfish around. Good chance to spot bigger fellows like sharks or napoleon wrasses as well...

text.description1: Although generally less dived than its northern counterpart (Miyaru Faru), Gulhi corner is a good option when oceanic current runs from the south east. A nice place to finish the dive after crossing the channel (coming from Myraru Faru corner). Some small overhangs with nice hard & soft corals. plenty of pelagics.
text.description2: Schools of eagle rays, white tip sharks, grey reef sharks, hawksbill & green turtles, marble & feather tail stingrays, napoleon wrasse, dogtooth tunas, reef fish.

text.description1: One of the best dive sites in this area, it offers almost everything. Top Reef 5 Meters , excellent for safety stop. Big overhangs with fantastic coral life, schooling fishes and predators wich hunt for them . Negative decent needed if there is current
text.description2: Grey Reefsharks, barracudas, white tip reefsharks, groupers, sweetlipps and many more - basically and if you are lucky all the stars of the underwater world might be there!

text.description1: Bathala Maga Khan Thila is a legend among divers in North Ari Atoll. Located at the entrance of the Bathala channel it is facing the Ocean in way to create perfect conditions for Grey Reefsharks and napoleonfishes...
text.description2: The reef starts from around 7 meters in the south and ends up at a depth of 30 meters. Strong currents can occur from time to time.

text.description1: Bolifushi Wreck is a around 60 ft long steel wreck which stands literally upright in the water with its bow on the top. The wreck is located between 4 to 20 meters of depth...
text.description2: The hard coral growth at the wreck is quite impressive. Also some soft corals are growing in the shade. Colorful tropical fishes as well as lionfish can be found easily...

text.description1: In the local language (Dhivehi), Miyaru means “shark“ and Faru means “reef“. Shark’s reef it is then, so it’s not too hard to guess what you can expect here!! White tip sharks galore, grey reef sharks aplenty, a few nurse sharks, less common leopard sharks too and even rare tiger sharks & whale sharks sightings!
text.description2: Turtles (both green & hawksbill) can be seen, along with schools or solitary eagle rays, rare bump head parrotfish, stingrays, huge napoleon wrasse and even pods of dolphins!

text.description1: This dive site is a channel located in the southern region of Vaavu atoll. The dive is a mixture of an outer channel where you can spot large pelagics and the inner reef wall where you can see lots of colorful coral life.
text.description2: At the mouth of the channel, when the current is medium to strong, you will spot sharks and big game fish cruising past. Inside the channel you will find all sorts of fish life.

text.description1: Surrounding Reef of Bulaloghi, an inhabited Island . Depending on current right or left should along the wall which has many caverns full wit corals and fish life
text.description2: All kind of schooling fish, fuesiliers, jacks, thunas, soldierfish, sweetlips and sleeping baby white tip reefs sharks. Eagle rays are frequent sighting

text.description1: Small Thila. Top at about 7 Meters, lots so re-growing stone corals, black corals in the deep part. Especially in current challenging as negative decent is needed away from the site.
text.description2: Lot of schooling fishes , grey reef sharks, eagle rays and whitetip reefsharks are frequent sightings there . All member of scorpionfish family so watch out where you hold on.

text.description1: Hohola Thila is a small Thila with an amazing rich underwater life. The highlights are the blue, red and orange frogfish and it is not unusual to see them swimming across the reef top. So keep your video ready. But also, the reef gives you plenty of other interesting things to discover, like a large group of batfishes.
text.description2: You can dive the Thila as you like. For sure you will dive one time around it. At the east side you will find a coral block connected through a saddle with the main reef.

text.description1: Rangali Madivaru (Madi = Manta, Faru = long Reef)  is a manta cleaning station located in the channel at approx. 9 meters on the edge where the sloping bottom meets a plateau reef. This dive site is best visited with the outgoing current.
text.description2: Manta rays can be seen at the cleaning station during the northeast monsoon season (Dec - April). Lots of fish, here is also a good site for macro life.

text.description1: Turtle Reef is a beautiful part of the outside reef on the east side of the atoll, famous for it turtle encounters. The reeftop stretches down to approximately 7 meters on the edge - after that the deep blue awaits you...
text.description2: Turtle reef is not only home for a healthy amount of hawksbill turtles. It also shelters a lot of anemones with clownfish, as well as huge schools of humpback snappers...

text.description1: Velassaru Caves is a beautiful spot on the outside reef of south Male Atoll’s northern tip. The name is given by the dive site location in combination with several overhangs spreading from depth levels between 10 to 30 meters.
text.description2: Due to its prime location in the channel between two atolls Velassaru Caves offer everything from the smallest macro organisms up to the chance of spotting even big pelagic fellows...

text.description1: This is a great site for beginning divers and advanced alike. This house reef is easily accessible from shore and filled with marine life.
text.description2: Watch turtles feeding on the reef while reef sharks swim by. There are also many angelfish, triggerfish, and schools of sweetlips.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Stingray City is quite misleading for a place where Nurse Shark dominate - Several separate coral block in depth from 15 to 3 are located in a small lagoon close to Embudu Channel.
text.description2: Stingray City is the must go for an unforgettable Nurse Shark experience! Either diving, snorkeling or mermaiding! Action guaranteed!

text.description1: Small Giri (shallow reef platform) located in a system of many Giris. The reef top is at 1-3m and slopes gently down. You can cross from one Giri to the other but the visibility is not very good usually.
text.description2: The hard coral life there is very good. Many species of Acropora and Massive Corals can be found. Fish life is quite good as well. Good for macro life.

text.description1: This dive site is located on the outskirts of Fesdhoo Island and embodies a wreck next to a small thila (pinnacle). This site is better suited for nitrox divers.
text.description2: Great for macro lovers, those who enjoy beautiful healthy corals, and lovers of large fish schools. This site is also known to be an occasional manta cleaning station.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: Embudu Express is famous for its current which can be up to 5-6 knots at times. Divers first go down straight to the edge in the middle of the channel and wait at 25-30m. The sharks and eagle rays come closer and closer.
text.description2: Possible sightings are hammerheads and guitar sharks, grey reef and white tip reef sharks, eagle rays and stingrays, big barracudas, and groupers, plus schools of jackfish and napoleon wrasse.

text.description1: This is a marine protected area because of the population of grey reef and white tip sharks it supports. The dive starts on the south side of the channel and then sinks down to the edge of the last “step” around 30m.
text.description2: Grey reef sharks, white tip reef sharks, napoleon wrasse, eagle rays, dog tooth tunas, leopard sharks, stingrays, and turtles (green & hawksbill) are all seen here.

text.description1: Fotteyo Kandu is considered by many as one of the best dive sites in the Maldives. This site is only for those divers who are experienced with strong currents and who are certified in deep diving.
text.description2: This channel dive site is home to many sharks, here you can see schools of grey reef sharks, along the reef you might see white-tip reef sharks, and look out for the elusive hammerhead!

text.description1: Moofushi Kandu is one of the prime channels in the Maldives to observe Grey Reef Sharks, Mantas, Eagle Rays and other big fellows. The channel entrance has a depth of 40 to 50 Meters. Crossings are only available at moderate currents
text.description2: On good days more than 100 Grey Reef Sharks are patrolling in front of the channel. Lucky divers have the chance to observe them from the top on good days...

text.description1: Also known as Moofushi Manta Point, this spot is fantastic for manta rays from December till April. The dive can be extended with a nice drift along the reef wall.
text.description2: Manta rays from December till April, this cleaning station also gets visited by white tip reef sharks, napoleon wrasse, mobula ray and eagle rays.

text.description1: Once this dive site was on the top 10 best in the world. Due to this rating many divers dived this site and specially at night. The damage on the top of this Thila (diver error) is bad, but as from 12m acceptable. At night many giant trevally and some white tips hunting.
text.description2: The deep pinnacles around the Thila are amazing with many grey reef sharks around and full of glass fish.

text.description1: This dive site is located near the island of Moofushi and is for advanced or deep certified divers, the top reef starts at 18-20 meters and the pinnacle itself is long and narrow.
text.description2: This drift dive is a great spot for gorgonian sea fans and soft corals. Here you will discover some fantastic macro life. This is also a great location for grey reef sharks.

elements.copyright: SUN  SIYAM  DIVING  OLHUVELI, 2005 South Male  Atoll

text.description1: One of the most popular dive sites in South Male Atoll due to healthy corals and amazing fish life. There are olorful hard corals, soft corals, and fans on a series of large overhangs. Do not miss the narrow passageway between the broken block and the main reef known as Called Canyon.
text.description2: Grey reef sharks, white tip reef sharks, nurse sharks, turtles, eagle rays, leaf fishes, dogtooth tunas, napoleon wrasse and the special guest appearance of whale sharks.

text.description1: Himandhoo Thila is located in the channel between the islands of Himandhoo and Moofushi. There is some interesting topography here with nice canyons and overhangs. Although this site is possible for all levels, beware of the current as it can get very strong.
text.description2: Come in the Northeast monsoon (Dec - Apr) for a chance to spot manta rays. Other species include grey reef sharks, barracuda, sweetlips, nudibranch, turtles and napoleon wrasse.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: A spectacular dive site located in the south-east of Hilton Maldives Amingiri. Giraavaru Caves is located at a channel mouth and can therefore be affected by strong currents. The dive site itself is most interesting in between 5 and 25 meters where it is dominated by caves and overhangs.
text.description2: The views from inside the caves and caverns are simply beautiful! You will see sharks but also eagle rays, napoleon wrasses and a lot of snappers.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Moon Valley is located very close to Kuda Haa in the same channel to the south-east of Hilton Maldives Amingiri. Moon Valley is situated directly at the channel mouth. Moon Valley is a great channel dive site that is often conducted as a (gentle) drift dive along a wall.
text.description2: During the months of January to April you’ll have great chances to see mobulas here. Eagle rays and napoleon wrasses all year round.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Dragon’s Mouth is an old time classic (and also favourite) that is located on the outside reef of North Male Atoll. The dive site itself is a well-protected inlet on the outside reef offering a number of caves.
text.description2: The most beautiful caves covered in sponges and soft corals are located at depths in between 10 and 15 meters.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Kuda Haa consists of two connected thilas that can easily be spotted from the surface. One thila starts at 6 meters and the other one at around 14 meters. Both of them slope down to a sandy bottom at 30+ meters. Kuda Haa is a legendary site which many divers have dubbed as fish soup.
text.description2: Napoleon wrasses, big blue tunas, moray eels, shrimps and basslets, scorpion fish or a mantis shrimps.

text.description1: Hafza Thila AKA Angotti is a small Thila located in the North Ari Atoll and famous for it’s stationary grey reef sharks, which can be seen on almost every dive.
text.description2: With the reeftop being as deep as 12 meters, divers need to be well organized and ready to descent on command. Once at the reef it is a easy place to dive...

text.description1: Laguna Matata is as the name suggests the Lagoon of Happiness. The happiness there is simply provided by colorful coral block in all huge variety of shapes and an abundant marine life.
text.description2: In depth levels from 1 to 15 meters a healthy hard coral life with a lot fishy surprises awaits you - some are very tiny and other rather big:-)

text.description1: Also known as Blue Caves, this thila dive site is famous for its amazing array of blue and purple soft corals. The name comes from the large overhangs which you can easily swim inside of and have a look around.
text.description2: Other than the magnificent coral life, here you can enjoy large schools of blue-striped snapper, interesting macro life, as well as grey reef sharks and white tip reef sharks.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: The Maldives Victory is a cargo ship that sank in 1981 just off of the island of Male City and the airport island. This 80m long cargo ship sunk while on its way from Singapore carrying goods for the resort islands.
text.description2: This site is great for macro lovers and lovers of wrecks, due to the current that flows through the channel there can be lots of fish surrounding the wreck.

text.description1: Underwater Habitat created by Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives is a unique project under the lead of our Resident Marine Biologist Sam Whiting in cooperation with our Dive Team Leader “Kudo“ who has more than 17 000 dives in the Maldives on his records...
text.description2: At depth levels from 1 to 14 meters with a gentle beach entrance Underwater Habitat by Sub Oceanic is easily accessible for Divers and Snorkelers alike.
