text.description1: Amin Faru is the barrier reef of Amingiri facing the open ocean which is often simply referred to as outside reef. It’s starts from around 5 meters and drops down several 100 meters in several stages...
text.description2: Due to its location between 2 channels there is a good chance to encounter bigger marine life like reef sharks, eagle rays napoleons and sometimes even Manta Rays...

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: What seems to be a rather “unspectacular” sandbank reveals itself as a very pretty dive site. Having said that, sandbanks are never really unspectacular in the Maldives but you wouldn’t expect a very pretty wall ranging from 3 to 30 meters when looking at the pristine white sand on top of the reef.
text.description2: You can expect to see a lot of curious batfish, many snappers, both blue striped and red snappers. Keep your eyes open for leopard sharks, white tips, and lobsters.

text.description1: This dive site is 10 minutes from hulhumale’. This is the south east reef of the airport.gentle slope starting from 2 meters,Reef edge between 3-5 meters sloping to 30 meters+
text.description2: Schools of fusilliers, Banner fish, Morey eel, Eagle rays, blacktip,white tip reef shark,surgeon fish, napoleone ..etc.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: The dive site is of round shape and can be defined as a classical Maldivian thila – a submerged pinnacle. The top reef is located at 4 meters which makes it easy to descent to for all experience levels.
text.description2: You will find a lot of anemones and of course also anemone fish. You’ll also find schooling bannerfish, glass fish blocks, turtles, stingrays ans jack fish.

properties.name: Neru Faru - Hilton Maldives Amingiri Housereef

text.description1: A beautiful hard coral reef right in front of Hilton Maldives Amingri welcomes divers of all levels at depth from 2 to 25 meters. Located in a channel the dive changes its character depending on the prevailing current direction and strength...
text.description2: Be prepared to meet tons of colorful reef fishes, clouds of glass fishes as well as leaf fish and stone fish.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Hulangu Kandu is located in the channel just north of Hilton Maldives Amingiri. The dive site itself sits at the corner of the outer reef. It is an interesting diving spot with changing reef structures.
text.description2: Hulangu Kandu on an incoming current is a classic shark dive. Watch large schools of grey reef sharks and white tips circling the deep waters.

text.description1: Rasdhoo is an interesting site with the wall of the island of Rasdhoo on one side and massive coral blocks (or thilas) mounted on the outside steep drop-off of the atoll. These two features create a corridor of sand between the inner reef and outer thilas. In some places, the corridor is only 20 meters wide.
text.description2: The thilas provide encounters with hunting jacks and trevally, white-tip and grey reef sharks, eagle rays, and occasionally manta rays.

text.description1: Suitable only for advanced divers, the channel between Kuramathi Resort Island and Rasdhoo offers world-class encounters between 22 and 30 meters deep. This dive works best with a medium current pushing mainly across and slightly in toward the atoll. Divers should follow the edge of the channel.
text.description2: Rasdhoo Channel features schools of grey reef sharks, white tips, stingrays, napoleons, turtles, eagle rays, groupers, snappers, and sometimes surprise guests (incl. guitarfish & mantas).

text.description1: Situated south of Kuramathi, a short two minute drive from the resort’s arrival and excursion jetty, divers are often at Fan reef, it is an easy wall dive and perfect for beginners and Open Water Divers. Most of the good stuff can be seen at shallow depths. However it is also by what they can see so close to shore.
text.description2: In the bays we often find Whitetipsharks sleeping and Blacktips patrolling. Deeper, you will find yourself in Fan Coral paradise. Sightings of Eagle Rays, Barracudas or Napoleons are frequently seen.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Located just north of Hilton Maldives Amingiri. This dive site is situated in the backdrop of a channel and just east of our dive site Hulangu Kandu. Due to its location strong currents can affect it. The site consists of a thila with three top reefs at 3 meters. The sandy bottom lies at around 20 to 30 meters.
text.description2: Nudibranchs, anemone fish, squad shrimp, sea stars and cleaner shrimp. Hunting tunas, jack fish and eagle rays. You will also find white tips lazing about and sting rays sleeping.

text.description1: Rasdhoo Madivaru is a channel located at the intersection of the local islands of Rasdhoo and Madivaru. Dive along the edge of parallel or perpendicular reef formations across the channel and explore the sandy areas.
text.description2: The channel offers great opportunities to spot sharks and larger fish along the edge and in the blue. In the sandy area, you can often spot various species of rays and resting sharks.

text.description1: Hammerhead Shark Point is situated in front of Madivaru, although the sharks can be encountered as far south as Kuramathi, east and in front of Rasdhoo, or anywhere in the blue or even reef side. Some luck is clearly involved in spotting these majestic creatures and there is not only one way to dive the shark point.
text.description2: The sparkling blue plankton lights the path at sunrise and the surgeonfish accompany divers and the bubbles. Hover in the deep and wait for the hammerheads to appear from the depths.

text.description1: Ory Faru is a great dive site situated right in front of Kuramathi island. This is an easy wall dive and perfectly suitable for all levels of divers. The reef starts at about 4 meters and drops down below 40 meters depth.
text.description2: While on top and inside the wall and reef you can spot octopus, lobsters, maldivian clown fish, moray eels and sometimes turtles, keep an eye in the blue for eagle rays and sharks.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Located a 10-minute boat ride north-east of Hilton Maldives Amingiri, Mas Giri is one of our must-see dive sites if you like beautiful marine life. Pretty much all tropical reef fish that are home in the Maldives can be found on Mas Giri.
text.description2: Expect to see turtles, white tip reef sharks, lionfish, lobsters, parrotfish, butterfly fish, damsels, surgeon fish, angel fish, rabbit fish, anemone fish, snappers, sweetlips, ....

text.description1: This dive site starts as a wall dive and leads into the channel, here you can enter the channel to enjoy a deeper dive or stay on the drop off point of the channel where you can enjoy all the fish life in the current.
text.description2: With the right current here you can encounter a whole array of fish in one place, from a shiver of grey reef and white tip reef sharks, to schools of tuna and jack, napoleon, and eagle rays.

text.description1: This is a suitable area for Try Dives and confined water training dives. It is at the public beach of Rasdhoo near the harbor. There is a sandy spot for kneeling.
text.description2: The divesite it at the reeftop of Rasdhoo. Many different species can be found here, including reef sharks, eagle rays and turtles.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll
Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Kudabe Thila is a large Thila with a top reef at 15 meters. The north side drops down in a steep manner until 50 meters and more whereas the south side is more of a steady gradient slope... Its location in the channel can make it tricky to dive from time to time.
text.description2: At Kudabe Thila one is able to spot large schools of blue-striped yellow snappers, fusiliers, humpback snappers, and many more. With the right current bigger fellow also show up...

properties.name: Gaa Huraa Kandu / Van Huraveli Kandu

text.description1: This channel located in the north of Meemu atoll offers a wide variety of marine life. If the current is not too strong you can cross the whole channel during the dive.
text.description2: This channel has nice colorful soft corals as well as grey reef sharks, white tip reef sharks, nurse sharks and schools of silver jacks.

text.description1: Three Palms offers a quiet dive along a wall with 3 beautiful formations of table corals which gives this spot its name. On the top of the house reef you can see blacktip reef sharks, in the channel eagle rays, and sometimes reef mantas. On the wall are also lionfish, lobsters, and a lot of small fish!
text.description2: The number of species is extremely high, both amongst the fish and corals. Most corals here are hard corals.

text.description1: This dive site is located at the harbour of Rasdhoo and suitable for confined water training. There are stairs leading into the water from the pier. Please always use a surface marker buoy.
text.description2: This divesite is near the pier of the Rasdhoo harbour. Above the sandy bottom sometimes reef sharks, stingrays and even eagle rays are passing by.

text.description1: This 40m long supply boat was sunk in 1987. Resting at a maximum depth of 20m, this site is perfect for all diving levels and, due to its sheltered location, makes a great night dive.
text.description2: Best for macro lovers or lovers of night dives, here you will spot many different species of crab, shrimp, lobster, as well as a large resident moray eel and often stingrays in the sand.

text.description1: Boduga means big block in Dhivehi. This site derives its name from the large coral block that sits just 2 meters under the surface at the end of the island of Kuramathi near the sandbank.
text.description2: This block is enveloped in reef fish. Descending from the block, you will find a sandy plateau at 25m where coral blocks litter the floor.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Black Coral consists of a long wall along a large circular shaped reef. The top starts at 4 meters and then descends to about 25m where you will find a sandy bottom. Due to its size, this reef has many different areas to explore. On the wall you will find lots of overhangs and even a small swim through.
text.description2: Long nosed hawkfish, ghost pipefish. Lots of puffer, box, trigger and angelfish forage around the reef.

text.description1: It is a dive for advanced divers with multiple logged dives and experience in deep diving, as you will be spending a lot of time in the blue water hanging at around 30m. The dive is in the middle of the ocean though you may start from the reef. High boat traffic. DSMB is a must.
text.description2: Multiple different species of mega fauna can be seen here including Tiger Sharks, Bull Sharks, Spinner Sharks, Lemon Sharks, Guitarfish, Giant Hammerheads, Grey Reef, etc.

text.description1: 5 min from Hulhumale Jetty, an extensive reef. It’s a steep slope starting at 3-5m down to 25m, and then where it has a sandy bottom at 30m+. the further you got away from the the reef the deeper it gets. This dive site normally doesn’t have current. Please use an SMB when ascending as there is alot of boat traffic.
text.description2: Hammerhead, tigershark, bullshark, spinner shark, lemonshark, nurseshark, guitarfish, bowmouth guitarfish, a few stingrays, eagle rays, jackfish, surgeonfish, and many more.

text.description1: The turtle reef is on the east side outside of the atoll, between Madivaru and Veligandu. Sometimes there is a nice ocean current making is very suitable for drift dives.
text.description2: This reef is famous for the many sea turtles feeding here on the reeftop and the reef slope. Often reef sharks, stingrays and eagle rays can be found in this area.

text.description1: Outside Hulhumale’ harbour - north of ferry entrance.
text.description2: Stingrays, tiger shark, hammerhead shark, guitarfish, spinner shark, whitetip reefshark, blacktip reefshark.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Located south of the resort island Baros. Baros Thila has a top reef at around 8 meters. The reef top is dominated by rock formations. From there it gradually slopes down to 25 to 28m.
text.description2: Expect many big magnificent sea anemones. . As soon as the big-nosed unicorn fish find you and your buddy they will start playing and enjoying themselves

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Located just north of Amingiri. This dive site lies in the protection of a faru in between two channels. This makes the dive sites less exposed to strong currents and therewith suitable for all experience levels. The reef structure is a thila from 4 to 30 meters.
text.description2: Neygey Thila is also known as Hoholha Gaa in Divehi, the local language of the Maldives. Translated to English it means “rock with overhangs” and this is exactly what you find here.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Baros Faru is a beautiful reef with healthy hardcoral life, located on the southern end of Baros’ lagoon. The landscape is very distinctive as the bottom of the reef merges with and endless coral garden at around 25 meters of depth.
text.description2: Beside stunning coral life this place is home to whitetip reef sharks, turtles and a lot nemos. Lionfishes and many other fishes can be found as well...

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Kuda Madi Giri means as much as “Little Ray Reef“ . The name comes from the frequently seen young stingrays there. The reef starts from a depth of 1 meter and drops down to around 25 meters on the sides...
text.description2: A stunning reef with 4 different faces! Each side is different. The west has one of the most amazing hard corals one can imagine and the east side stunning swim throughs and fish life

text.description1: These caves are located on the western end of the atoll past the Kuramathi Resort sandbank. There are many large overhangs here, but also two caves through which divers can swim (one at 18-20 meters, the other at 28-30 meters).
text.description2: In the caves and overhangs, you may find white tips, stingrays, or nurse sharks. Very healthy coral on top of the reef at 5 meters.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: The legendary Banana Reef! The reef is big and banana-shaped with caves and overhangs. The reef top is between 3 to 8 meters from where it drops to 30+ meters.
text.description2: A surprising variety of schooling fish and large pelagic. Amongst the large overhangs resides an enormous school of blue-striped snappers.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Shews Thila is the extension of the close by main reef. The top starts at around 2 meters and drops down in stages to 30 meters in most areas. A perfect place for treasure hunters...
text.description2: Shews Thila is not the classical coral reef as one might imagine, however where coral life shines through it is absolutely stunning and full of surprises...

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Lao Fu Thila is a deep topped Thila (24 meter) accessed by a short ride from Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives, perfect for divers with a deep diving certification. Its location close to a channel provides a flow of current which brings a fresh flow of nutrients to support the abundance of fish life on the Thila.
text.description2: Lao Fu Thila has an astounding abundance of shoaling fish: covered in shimmering glassfish, huge clouds of fusiliers and armies of surgeonfish!

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll
Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Iru Thila is a small free standing reef on the west side of North Male Atoll. Starting from the topreef at 7 meters it drops down to around 30 all around
text.description2: Iru Thila is nicely located close to a channel which ensures a healthy exchange of nutritions throughout. The highlight of the place are it’s huge black coral trees!

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Bandos Rock is located on the house reef of Bandos Island Resort. The top reef starts at 3 to 5 meters and drops (rather steeply) to a sandy bottom at 30+ meters. You will find several caves and interesting overhangs on the wall. Enjoy the large table corals, the pinnacle and a canyon.
text.description2: Black and white tip reef sharks, tunas and sometimes even eagle rays. Inside the caves and overhangs you can find lobsters, cleaner shrimps, lionfish, and moray eels.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Jemima Giri is a very beautiful, classical Maldivian Giri. It is named after a young female diver who first dove the place. Starting from 0.8 meters the reef gradually slopes down to its maximum depth of around 20 meters.
text.description2: Jemima Giri is dominated by hard corals either integrated on the main reef or as separated blocks along the sandy bottom. A great place to see various types of stingrays...

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Toti Thila is a small reef with its reeftop starting at around meters. It’s drops down on all sides to around 30 meters where the corals meet the seabed. Toti Thila is named after the Instructor who first discovered it - Toti!
text.description2: Huge black coral trees and a interesting topography with a few arms leading away from the reef makes this place very interesting for special marine encounters...

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Sara Thila is a beautiful seamount with its topreef starting from 12 meters and reaching the sandy bottom from 25 to 40 meters. Depending on the side of the Thila. Sara Thila is named after a female dive instructor who was the first in history to submerge at this place...
text.description2: Sara Thila is a seamount build up in different levels with some plateaus and engulfed sand patches. Beautiful hard coral blocks, as well as huge black corals are dominating the site...

text.description1: This dive site has many names, Fish Tank, Fish Factory, Stingray City and they all fit! There is actually a fish factory on the island and this is the reason why there are so many rays and moray eels.
text.description2: Here you can see almost all types of moray eels, giant, leopard, yellow head, sooty head, reticulated moray eels, to name but a few. Also stingrays, black-spotted rays and mangrove rays.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: The dive site is a classical channel dive site that also features a thila, which is an underwater mount from 12 to 30 meters. Usually jumped on the outside reef with a left shoulder drift into the channel. After approximately 20 meters it is possible to reach the thila.
text.description2: Mantas, dog tooth tuna in packs, giant trevally, white tip and grey reef sharks riding the current and huge schools of fusiliers. Many napoleons and gliding eagle rays.

text.description1: This cleaning station is located quite far inside the north channel of the atoll. The cleaning station is at just 12m depth and surrounded by a sandy bottom, making it perfect to kneel down at a distance to watch the manta ray cleaning show.
text.description2: Relax at the bottom to watch the manta rays soar overhead. Let the manta rays come to you, don’t swim after them. Here you can also see schools of fish and tropical marine life.

text.description1: North Channel on the north/north-east side of Rasdhoo Atoll. The channel is relatively shallow and with average depth of 20 m is suitable for competent open water divers. The current can get quite strong here, so choosing the right time to visit is important.
text.description2: Mantas can be seen at several shallow cleaning stations in the channel. Outside of Manta Season this is a great spot for honeycomb moray eels, stingrays, lionfish, leaf fish, whitetips.

text.description1: Probably one of the best Thilas in the whole North Male area, also known as Paradise Rock or Virgin Reef. There are several pinnacles on the north of the Thila, where the main fish are, along with beautiful coral formations and sea fans. Wonderful dive for experienced divers due to the strong current.
text.description2: Sharks, napoleons, turtles, barracudas, schools of black snapper or fusiliers, but keep one eye also for the macro stuff in these amazing soft corals.

text.description1: The divesite is located in the north outside of the atoll. It is a vertical wall that continues in a reef slope at 25+ m. With some current a nice drift dive can be done. This dive is a good alternative should there be no manta at the cleaning station.
text.description2: There are often encounters with reef sharks, mobula rays, eagle rays and even dolphins. On the top reef schools of sweetlips and other reef fish can be found.

text.description1: This amazing reef are 3 blocks. The biggest begins in the south between 80-100m long and it's full of corals, it would be nice we can start here. In the east we have another wonderful block a bit similar to east block Maya Thila covert full with corals. In the north is the smallest block. AOW or higher
text.description2: Full with Snapper, Jacks and Fusiliers hunted by white tip or black tip reef sharks. In the blue passing gray reef sharks, barracudas.

text.description1: The divesite is located at the northernmost point of the Rasdhoo atoll. There is a reef wall between 10-25 m and a reef slope descending into the deep water.
text.description2: The name of the divesite means shark reef, a good description as often reef sharks, eagle rays and mobula rays can be found here.

text.description1: Cool drift dive that also always brings current with it. Start either near the Manta Point or, with less current, directly at the channel entrance. The caves are rather overhangs that range from 12 to 30m. For the more experienced there is a deep nose in the middle of the current.
text.description2: A place where you can see with a little luck almost everything. mantas, mobulas, napoleons, grey reef sharks, white tip and black tip reef sharks, and with a lot of luck a hammerhead shark.

text.description1: Thinga Thila is the Divehi name for Lion Seamount. Due to the high amount of big lionfishes on the southeast side of the Reef the name makes very much sense. Thinga Thila is a true treasure box for photographers and explorers. One highlight after the next one...
text.description2: Starting from as shallow as 3 meters the reef slopes gently down to the seabed at around 30 meters. Several types of shrimps, moray eels and hundreds of bannerfish are awaiting you...

text.description1: Lankan is a cleaning station for manta rays and scuba divers visiting often get to see an amazing manta show, one of the highlights of any trip to the Maldives.
text.description2: Besides the mantas, you will find sharks, mobulas, eagle rays, stingrays, napoleons, morays, and a lot of fish.

text.description1: Nice drift dive for all levels of divers. After Manta season we dive here to watch other amazing life. The reef slopes from 5 to 30m down, deeper on the bottom, sharks and stingrays are found in the sandy areas. In the big rocks, we see groupers and glass fish.
text.description2: So much to see! Sharks, jacks, bat fish, snappers, grouper, morays eagle rays, and stingrays.

text.description1: Located on the northeastern side of Meedhoo island, this dive site has a lot to offer. A sloping reef full of small coral blocks which are the perfect hideaway for moray eels and masters of camouflage. Such as leaf and scorpion fish. You will also find some anemones with not only clownfish, but also porcelain crab
text.description2: Moray eels, leaf and scorpion fish. You will also find some anemones with not only clownfish, but also porcelain crab. Grey Reef Sharks, Snappers, Groupers, white tip sharks

text.description1: Sunlight Thila is a formation of two small reefs that attract giant manta rays between March and October. Between the reefs lies a 60-meter long sandy bottom boasting small coral formations with plenty of cleaner wrasses.
text.description2: Nearby the coral blocks we find schooling reef fishes, turtles, trigger and some macro stuff, but most come to see the gentle mantas!!

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Rasgefaanu Thila is the translation of Emperor Mountain. Emperor mountain refers to the first lady who ever submerged there - Ms. Kaiser or in English Ms. Emperor
text.description2: The divesite starts at a depth of around 7 meters and is one of the places with the highest biodiversity in the atoll as well as home of countless stonefish...

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Bodu Thila means Big Seamount in local language - however, it is actually only a small seamount. Starting from a depth of 2meters on the top the reef drops down to a depth of around 25 meters. The southside of the Thila has a lot of nice overhangs with a lot of macro life to discover...
text.description2: Beside beautiful hard corals and the common Maldivian marine life Bodu Thila also hosts a school of very curious batfish who love to follow divers:-)

text.description1: This dive site is a wreck to the west of Meemu Atoll. The wooden wreck of a transportation dhoni rests on the south side of the Giri at 20 - 33 m deep. It is approx. 30 m long and sank in 1979. It is easy to dive inside. The Giri is adorned with interesting overhangs and many small caves and caverns.
text.description2: You will find groupers, moray eels, rock cods, and glassfish. Spectacular soft coral gardens and dense shoals of fish in all shapes, sizes, and colors make this dive one to remember.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Kandu Thila is located north of Hilton Maldives Amingiri in Rasfari Channel. Due to its location in a channel, Kandu Thila can experience very strong currents which makes it a dive site that is suitable more for the advanced diver.
text.description2: The reef is covered with plenty of hard corals which are beautiful to look at with all the schooling fish, moray eels, anemones, giant trivially and groupers.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Rasfari Corner, which is located directly at the channel mouth, ranges from 9 to 30 meters and is an interesting drift dive. During the dive you will make your way along the reef, explore rocks, little overhangs, coral blocks and maybe even the two deeper reefs off the main reef corner.
text.description2: Rasfari Corner is known for a great chance to see big grey reef sharks, barracudas, eagle rays and schools of jack fish. It is an amazing dive site that is often visited by dolphins.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Mas Thila is located just in the backdrop of Kandu Thila. The reef top is located at 8 meters. From there the reef drops to about 30 meters.  “Mas” translates into “fish” in Divehi, the language of the Maldives, and this is what you will get here.
text.description2: Tunas and large barracudas can be spotted at Mas Thila as well big schools of fusiliers, snappers and banner fish.

text.description1: Himmafushi Corner offers a wonderful drift dive on an easy slope from 5 to 30m. Here there is a drop-off and you can see big life with a bit of luck.
text.description2: On top of the reef you will find morays, fusiliers, snapper, turtles, and small stuff. Deeper you meet Whitetip reef sharks, napoleons, and eagle rays.

text.description1: Himmafushi Corner is a drift dive, best suited for divers with a lot of experience as this dive is deep and can have strong currents. The corner slopes from 5 to 30m and after that comes to a small drop off to 45/50m. This dive should only be conducted during the incoming current.
text.description2: In the strong current you can have a lot of pelagics: grey reef sharks, schools of jacks and tunas, napoleons and different rays.

text.description1: Really nice drift dive on a sloping wall and blocks in the more sloping area full of soft corals and marine life. It starts at 4 to 5 meters and goes down to 30+ meters and is one side of a channel. You can expect current but not too strong.
text.description2: This site is part of a channel so you may see nurse sharks, eagle rays, jacks and wonderful small stuff as well in the soft coral, like shrimp, crab, nudibranchs, and lobster.

text.description1: One of the most colorful dive sites on North Male Atoll. On the south side of Girifushi Island, this site has abundant fish life and very nice soft corals. There are numerous blue soft corals and a swim through. The current can be strong!!
text.description2: Easy to find schools of jack and trevally, rainbow runners, barracuda, and tunas. Sometimes eagle rays and grey reef sharks are around as well.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Shark Point is located 45 minutes north west of Hilton Maldives Amingiri. The dive site promises a pleasant drift dive in depths from 10 to 30 meters along a pretty faru (long reef) close to Rasfari Corner.
text.description2: You might have guessed – at shark point sharks are starring the show and we can pretty much promise you an encounter with one of those elusive animals.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Neygey Thila is a very pretty dive site just south of Kuda Hithi. The thila actually consists of three separate humps that connect to each other in between 15 and 18 meters and then jointly drop to the sea bottom.
text.description2: You might find white tip reef sharks either hunting in the current or sleeping in the sand. Look into the overhangs and underneath coral blocks for sleeping nurse sharks.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Nakatcha Thila is a spectacular dive site.  Nakatcha Thila is a medium sized reef with magnificent overhangs and beautiful caves covered with a great variety of hard and soft corals.
text.description2: Napoleon wrasse and whitetip reef sharks, hawksbill turtles, spiny lobsters, groupers, snappers, gorgonians, angelfish, groupers.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Rasfari Beyru is located on the outside reef in between Shark Point and the Bodu Hithi Manta Point. This fact alone should tell you that it is a dive site with the greatest potential of making your day a really special one.
text.description2: Grey reef sharks, eagle rays, tuna, barracudas and schools of trevallies are often spotted here. The reef itself offers a wide variety of marine life making this their home.

text.description1: An easy dive site which is ideal for open water dives 3 and 4 OWD, but also offers nice macro stuff. You can find them at the mini wreck or the cargo that lies around the hull on the ground (16-19m). A little further out west (20m) we find a small thila.
text.description2: Sea needles, gobies, butterflyfish, young fusiliers, huge very shy turtles, warty snails, and, with a little luck, nudibranchs or huge stingrays!

text.description1: This site is known well for its manta cleaning station and feeding ground. Here, between December and April, manta rays come for cleaning or plankton feeding. This spot is great for diving and snorkeling.
text.description2: Here you can encounter manta rays getting cleaned by smaller fish, as well as stingrays and reef sharks. On occasion you may get a whale shark cruising by.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Bodu Hithi Manta Point is probably one of the best manta cleaning stations in North Male atoll. It requires a 60-minute (dive) boat ride to the north in order to reach the gentle giants. The station is active, alive and kicking during the northeast monsoon (December to April).
text.description2: Expect to see manta rays from December to April. If there are no mantas it is still a pleasant dive and it is possible to see sharks, turtles and many, many other colourful reef fish.

text.description1: Kani Thila is about 400m from Kani inside and should only be dived by experienced divers. It is already very deep and you must always keep an eye on the air supply. There are overhangs with black coral bushes and on the reef top there are bubble anemones.
text.description2: Beautiful shoals with fusiliers, banner fish and batfish. In the anemones you can find smallest shrimps and crabs. Big green turtles which are very shy.

text.description1: Easy but always nice dive. The top of the reef drops down from 7m to 30/35m and then runs into the sand. Depending on the current, you simply dive the right or left shoulder. With a little luck, this dive site offers everything that makes diving exciting!
text.description2: You may see mantas and alder rays, turtles, and blacktip reef sharks on the reef top, whitetip and grey reef sharks a little deeper.

text.description1: A well-protected dive site. The top of the reef is at 4m and is, therefore, also popular with snorkelers. Between 4-6m the wall begins to fall straight down. Many small inlets and crevices.
text.description2: In the crevices we find a lot of small things but also nurse sharks or stingrays and turtles. In the sandy ground they hunt for different species. Stingray species and whitetip reef sharks pass by.

text.description1: Kani Corner is basically a slope that goes to 25 - 30 m in a sandy bottom. There are some big blocks this deep and at the right time, mantas visit the blocks or pass by the top of the reef. The current can be strong so take caution.
text.description2: Here you can see at the right time mantas, eagle rays, stingrays, white tip reef sharks, grey reef sharks, Hammerheads, honeycomb and giant morays, turtles, and napoleons.

text.description1: This dive site is located right next to the island. The long reef ends into a corner of the canal. Here you can see several highlights. A very nice dive site for beginners as well as experienced divers.
text.description2: With a bit of luck, you will discover turtles, white tip, blacktip sharks, eagle rays, and napoleons. Also, depending on the season, mantas come to the reef.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: A small thila located in Hithi channel with medium to sometimes strong currents. It starts at about 13m, sloping down to a depth of 30 meters and more.
text.description2: Lots of reef fish such as butterfly fish, blennies, gobies and anemone fish are found all over the reef. Big groups of fusiliers can be seen passing while being hunted by trevallies.

text.description1: A great site of Thoddoo, located on the south-eastern part of the island. Suitable for both professionals and beginners, accessible practically all year round so that you won’t miss a thing :).
text.description2: The main attraction of this dive site is sharks (grey reef sharks and reef sharks). On the ridge of the corner, you can always find a turtle or two. Very often you can see eagle rays.

text.description1: The reef is one side from a canal between Lohifushi and Kani so you must expect also current. In this time its only for really experience divers. Without current you can do nice night dives on the house reef. The reef falls down from 6 to 40m.
text.description2: In the current dives will often encounter grey reef sharks, white tip sharks, nurse sharks, eagle rays and napoleons.

text.description1: This dive site is located on a very long coral wall in the south-western part of the island. The slope fully covered by hard corals. Perfect for beginners as the top part of the dive site is just 3 meters deep. Ideal for turtle spotting.
text.description2: The dive site speaks for itself. Turtles, turtles, turtles! Green turtles and hawskbills are very common here. Eagle rays, mobula rays and mantas are also quite often seen here.

text.description1: This is a typical channel dive, however, the down/up currents found here make for difficult conditions that are not suitable for the beginner diver.
text.description2: This is a place where everything is possible. Whitetip and blacktip reef sharks, grey reef sharks, eagle rays, batfish and butterflyfish, napoleon wrasse, and sometimes a big school of dolphins!

text.description1: This drift dive is a slope from 5 to 25m. Some big blocks are on the way. There you will find big turtles and sharks passing by. On top of the reef, you see parrotfish, napoleon, morays, and eagle rays.
text.description2: From small to big. Morays with cleaner shrimps on the top, grey reef sharks deeper, stingrays, and Mantas all over! You are guaranteed to see eagle rays and turtles.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic at Hilton Maldives Amingiri, 20188 North Male Atoll

text.description1: Bodu Hithi Thila is a two slightly separated seamounts in the famous Bodu Hithi Channel. Seasonally it is one of the top Manta Spots in North Male Atoll.
text.description2: Starting from around 7 meters the reefs drops down on the westerly side to around 30 meters and hosts a famous cleaning station for Mantarays at around 25 meters.

text.description1: The Big Cave is along Faru in the inner Atoll and is part of the Maldivian Marine Park. The dive leads through an endless cavern, which is about 10 m high and 15-30 m deep. Its inside is laced with soft corals, gorgonians, and assorted anemones.
text.description2: There are sting rays and sleeping white tip reef sharks in the white sand in front of the caverns. Many shoals of fish roaming arund the reef.

text.description1: This dive site is to the west of Veyvah Island. This site is suitable for divers of all training levels, having a large drop off on its southern side. It falls from 10 to 30 meters and is beautifully carpeted with soft corals and sponges. In the north, there are numerous overhangs at 15-25 meters.
text.description2: In the overhangs, you can spot moray eels, shrimp, scorpionfish, and dragonfish. Keep your eyes open for king mackerels and tunas roaming around in the open water.

text.description1: The top reef starts at 3m to 6m and fall as a wall down to 25/30m On this protected wall you will find a lot of small stuff but also bigger ones. The big ones are on the ground, in the small overhangs or in the mini cavern. nice and easy for all level
text.description2: The zebra or nurse sharks you will find with a bit of luck under the overhangs close to the ground. Its a nice place to find nudis or scorpion fish. Turtles are in the small columns

text.description1: 1000 Rocks is located within the marine nature reserve. The entry is north of the Faru. The sandy plateau falls from 5-15 meters and is sprinkled with lovely coral formations. From a depth of 18m onwards, there are large caverns beautifully decorated with many types of soft corals.
text.description2: Macro enthusiasts will find ideal conditions. Among the coral blocks, you can find rock cod, shrimp, and moray eels. In open water, there are large shoals of mackerel and fusiliers.

text.description1: The dive site “Chapati Thilas“consists of the main reef sloping into a sandy plateau, on which you find many small Thilas coming up to a depth of 15 m. The plateau ends in a big drop off at 25 m, going down to around 34 m. Roam around the Thilas to find sleeping rays or sharks on the sandy bottom.
text.description2: We can find glassfish, basslets, different types of butterflyfish, lionfish, moray eels, and sometimes even turtles. Out in the blue, you can find tunas, fusiliers, and bannerfish.

text.description1: This is a gently sloping reef, ideal for beginners and advanced divers. There are many large coral blocks on the reef. This site is great for night diving as well.
text.description2: Often seen are nurse sharks, baby white tip reef sharks, and blacktip reef sharks. In manta season, the Palm Reef also gives you the chance to dive with these gentle giants.

text.description1: Wave Giri lies west of Muleeh Island and is adorned with ledges begging you for being explored. The caves and ridges can mainly be found at a depth of 2 - 30 m. There are wonderful soft coral gardens. On the west side there are large coral formations at 12 - 15 m.
text.description2: The Giri offers a vide variety of fish, plenty of shrimp, glassfish, snails, moray eels, scorpionfish, and shoals of rock cod in all colors.

text.description1: This is a simple and relaxing dive for all levels of experience and skills. As indicated by the name, this dive site is divided into two parts - a wall dropping to roughly 23 m and a sandy plateau with many different coral blocks.
text.description2: The wall drops down from a depth of 5 - 23 m with lots of caverns and overhangs, where glassfish, moray eels, and different sponges can be found, also fusiliers, turtles and stingrays.

text.description1: One of Thoddoo best spots to dive with mantas. Located just in front of Sunrise bikini beach or 5 min boat ride from the harbor. Along the wall, there are some large formations of bell-shaped corals (the name of the dive site means Great Bells in Dhivehi).
text.description2: On the top of coral formation, there is a manta cleaning station. Corals are home for shrimps, crabs and lobsters. Among of other residents - green turtles and hawksbills.

text.description1: A small Giri to the west of Mulee Island. To the east side, at 10-25 m depth, there are beautifully overgrown ridges with a fine display of corals. The reef top is in perfect condition and there are plenty of large table corals and other hard corals to admire.
text.description2: Due to its geographical location, you will find big fish such as white tip and grey reef sharks, nurse sharks, groupers, tuna, and spectacular schools of mackerel and fusiliers.

text.description1: This wall is for all kind of divers, easy and protected but nice. The reef falls from 5 to 25m and we have to look in the small overhangs.In the right month (May to Aug) often mantas passing in the blue. A spot also good for a night dive and a good chance to get surprised.
text.description2: you will find turtles, nurse shark, scorpion fish, bat fish, flat worm and nudis, different shrimps but keep always one eye in the blue for the big stuff

text.description1: This small Giri lies to the west of Medhufushi Island and offers perfect dive conditions. The island is encircled with caverns at about 10 m, some reaching down to 30 m. The ridges and caverns are separated by a few sandy streches, where many fish can be found.
text.description2: The caverns are occupied by soldier fish, large rock cod, surgeon fish, sweet lips, and snappers. There are also sleeping sharks. Macro photographers will find everything they could wish for.

text.description1: This is a small Thila west of Veyvah Island. Since it is located in the inner atoll area, it is easy to dive here. From about 15 m there are drop offs and overhangs. In the west, there is a sandy plateau which is covered in coral formations. In the north, there are several large blocks of corals in front of the Thila.
text.description2: The coral blocks on and around Veyvah Thila are full of shrimp, nudibranchs, glassfish, and moray eels. Fusiliers can be found as well as sweet lips.

text.description1: “Bodu Securade“ is a long Faru inside the atoll. Along a nice drop off from 15 - 25 meters we have many overhangs and smaller caves, the walls are covered in soft corals and sponges, which dazzle with their variety of colors.
text.description2: In the overhangs you are likely to find glassfish, shrimp, various moray eels, and also leaf fish. It is also common to spot large shoals of fusiliers and hunting jackfish in the open water.

text.description1: This small Giri lies west of Medhufushi. It is covered in overhangs on the northwest side and has small caverns on the south side. There is a drop off from 10 - 30 m which stretches around the whole Giri. At a depth of 10 - 15 m there are large coral formations, which are full of marine life.
text.description2: Much shoaling fish can be found here, plus groupers, nudibranchs, shrimp, glassfish, and anemones. In open water there are hunting tuna and barracuda.

text.description1: A Thila southwest of Medhufushi. On its southwest side, at 10 - 15 m, there is a sandy plateau, which is covered in soft corals of all shapes and sizes. The eastern side has numerous caverns and overhangs to be explored at 15 - 30 m.
text.description2: Stingrays and whitetip reef sharks meander casually among the reef, macro lovers will be delighted to find glass fish, cleaner shrimp, nudibranchs, flatworms, sea stars, and sponges.

text.description1: 5 Palms is a fun drift dive that has something to offer for every level of diver. The top of the reef starts at 5m and drops down at 8m. At 22/25m there is a sandy plateau on the edge of which big fish appear from time to time.
text.description2: Besides the usual suspects like napoleons, whitetip reef sharks, sweetlips, perch, green turtles, and stingrays, you can see manta rays and mobulas at the right time.

text.description1: Colosseum is located on the west side of the island of Thulusdhoo. At the corner to the channel there is a large indentation in the form of a Roman amphitheatre at approx. 20m. This form is the epitome of the dive site and, at the same time, a meeting place for many marine creatures.
text.description2: Everything can swim in front of your mask here: reef sharks, turtles, tunas, jackfish, napoleons, mantas, stingrays, and possibly whale sharks and big hammerheads.

text.description1: This site is located off the northeast side of Mulah Island. 4 Reefs stretch out from NW to SE, with their reef tops between 5 and 10 m below the surface. In between those Thilas, you find narrow sandy passages (only 5 - 10 m wide on the narrowest point).
text.description2: Shoals of different kinds of fish, swetlips, humpback snappers, fusiliers, and sometimes stingrays or nurse sharks sleep on the sand. Out in the blue, there are barracudas and eagle rays.

text.description1: This wall is for all kinds of divers, easy and protected but nice. Here the top reef falls from 5 to 25m and there we have to look in the small overhangs for stingrays, turtles, and nurse sharks Sometimes you can find zebra sharks. In the right month there are often mantas passing in the blue.
text.description2: In the wall you see lobster, nudibranchs, scorpionfish, nurse sharks, and turtles. Eagle rays, blacktip reef sharks, and mantas passing in the blue. Near end you can also meet the batfish gang.

text.description1: Easy Express is a drift dive on the east side of Veyvah Island. On the wide reef top there are numerous coral formations with quite stunning anemonies. The steep drop pff at 12 - 30 m has plenty of overhangs.
text.description2: In the overhangs, you can find rock cod, napoleons, moray eels, and many other species. In open water there are large shoals of hunting jacks, king mackerel, passing eagle rays, and sharks.

text.description1: Viligili Corner is a really nice drift dive. The current can be really strong during the southwest monsoon and is precisely the best moment to dive here. It offers the best chance to gray reef or white tip sharks at the coral rocks at 25 meters.
text.description2: You will have a good chance to see different sharks close to the corner, stingrays, eagle rays, impressive napoleons, but also moray eels and their cleaner shrimp.

text.description1: Nice Drift dive for all level of divers. The reef slopes from 5 to 30m down, deeper on the ground laying sharks and stingrays in the sandy areas. In the big Rocks we see groupers and glas fish. On the top we find turtles, different kind of morays and a lot of fish.
text.description2: on this drift we will meet turtles, w-tip reef sharks, nice schools of fusiliers, nurse sharks, napoleons, and eagle rays.

text.description1: This dive site is located right in the middle of the channel, between “Mantas and More“ and “Sharks Tongue.“ The significant features of this dive site are the coral walls gently sloping down to 35 m which turn into a sheer drop to the blue ocean, offering a mass of overhangs to explore.
text.description2: In favorable currents there are masses of shoaling fish and often many different types of sharks as well. In the shallower levels towards the end of the dive there is an abundance of moray eels.

text.description1: An easy dive site, this Giri west of Medhufushi is free of currents. It´s known for the unbelievable beauty of the coral garden at 15 - 25 m, displaying soft, leather, and fan corals, as well as a big selection of sponges.
text.description2: Large overhangs in the east and south are inhabited by sweet lips and a large variety of rock cod. Shoals of fusiliers can be found all year round.

text.description1: Due to the currents, Sharks Tongue can become a tricky dive site, which requires some skills. “Sharks Tongue“ is located east of Mulah Island. Its highlight is the reef slope at 15 - 25 meters deep, which is the utmost in shark “dormitories“. With incoming current, you will often spot grey reef sharks and silvertips.
text.description2: Turtles and dense shoals of surgeonfish, oriental sweetlips, fusiliers, and copper snappers, black and whitetip reef sharks meander in between the coral blocks.

text.description1: This small Giri lies to the west of Medhufushi. The sandy plateau at 10 - 14 m is covered in coral formations; also there are huge overhangs full of soft corals, reaching down from 15 - 33 m. As the Giri is very protected, this dive site is suitable for all diving levels.
text.description2: Of particular interest are the many different species of perch to be found here. Stingrays are often seen on the sandy ground of the caverns.

text.description1: This is a top dive site in this area, located to the east of Mulee Island. During the season from December to May, it is possible to spot manta rays with their offspring, busying themselves around the numerous cleaning stations at 10 - 15 meters. The gentle slope from 15 - 30 meters is adorned with coral formations.
text.description2: This spot is a natural meeting ground for numerous big fish, such as barracudas, napoleons, sharks, rays, and tuna.

text.description1: A beautiful thila (pinnacle) to the west of Medhufushi Island. On the south side of the thila at 15 - 25 meters, there is a stunning display of soft coral. The dive site is remarkable due to a large number of beautifully adorned overhangs.
text.description2: Large numbers of rock cod, shoals of glassfish and fusiliers in all colors and sizes, sweet lips, turtles, lobster, and snappers can be spotted here as well.

text.description1: This dive site is along the outer reef side of the Faru. The structure of the reef is like a steep slope around 45°. From 30 m on the reef, it goes straight down like a wall.
text.description2: Groups of blue-lined or humpback snappers, fusiliers, sweetlips, and other shoaling fish. Turtles, tunas or sharks, sometimes you can spot a baby whitetip reef shark sleeping under a rock.

text.description1: This Giri lies very protected in the inner atoll, north of Hakura Island, and therefore is usually free of currents. On the northwest side, the drop-off falls to 30 m.
text.description2: Fusiliers, sweetlips, snappers, all kinds of perch, cod, groupers, and surgeonfish, as well as nudibranchs and cleaner shrimp. In open water, you might see tuna and white tip reef sharks.

text.description1: Triple Rock consists of 3 small Giris to the west of Medhufushi. At around 10 m deep, there are overhangs that reach over to the east. On the middle Giri we find soft corals and giant clams. On the southwest side, there is a plateau with large coral formations at 15 m. Marco photographers will be delighted.
text.description2: Magnificant shoals of fish inhabit this area, from fusiliers and surgeonfish to mackerel - you can find all kinds of fish here. Also, macro enthusiasts will be thrilled diving here.

text.description1: “Turtle Bay“ is the closest reef. This dive spot is just at the beginning of the inside atoll and the navigation is very easy. The reef goes down from 5 - 40 m and has a lot of overhangs.
text.description2: As the name is telling, a lot of turtles live here, as well as lionfish, glassfish, and whitetip reef sharks.

text.description1: The reef on the eastern side of Maalhaveli Island is a long Faru on the outer side of the atoll. This spot is located between “Boahura Express“ in the north and “Medhufushi Outside“ in the south. The top of the reef is about 8 - 10 m deep and continues in a 45° angle to 30 m.
text.description2: There´s a good chance of seeing turtles, sharks, tuna and all kinds of shoaling fish. Also, parrotfish, snappers, and surgeonfish can be found.

text.description1: This site is found on the outer reef of Medhufushi Island. An endless elongated Faru, the top of the reef is covered in coral blocks at roughly 30 m. There is also a big drop off going down til 50 m+.
text.description2: In shallow waters around 5 - 12 m there are turtles and large shoals of long nosed surgeon fish. On the steep outer reef at 12 - 33m there are white tips, barracudas, and hunting tuna.

text.description1: Finger Point also known as Kuda faru, the divesite is located in the channel of Makunudhoo, a few kilometers northwest of the island that shares the same name. The northern reef of the channel presents an interesting outgrowth, which looks like a pinnacle (Thila), has a top reef at 12m and is connected to the main reef.
text.description2: Similar to Manta rays when they attend the cleaning stations, gray reef sharks need the valuable assistance of wrasses to ensure hygiene. Divers should not disturb the sharks.

text.description1: Asdhoo Wreck is a small steel vessel located right next to the reef. Both the wreck and the reef can be explored in a single dive. As with all wreck dives, proper training and good buoyancy control is important.
text.description2: Schools of different types of fishes including snappers, bannerfish, fuesiliers and trevallies can be found. Other type of marine life on and around the wreck is quite good as well.

text.description1: West Rock is home to a small wreck that is easy to dive, which lies upright in a small bay at a depth of about 26m. Parts of the hold can be explored. The superstructure and the mast come down to 10m.
text.description2: Glass fish cavort in the hold as well as in the superstructure. A small school of Midnight Snapper stands depending on the current directly on the wreck or around the bow.

text.description1: This reef is located on the northwestern corner of the small Kurali Island in the southwest of Meemu Atoll. It slightly drops down to a depth of about 30 m and beyond.
text.description2: Very nice soft and hard corals on the reef top, where we can find big stingrays, turtles, and other shoaling fish. With a bit of luck and incoming current, you can find grey reef sharks.

text.description1: Located along a stand alone reef. There are several overhangs towards the East side of the reef that can be explored quite easily. Start the dive up current from the caves and put up the DSMB towards the end of the dive.
text.description2: Schools of fusiliers, Anemonefish, Macro Critters, different Types of Moray Eels, and Eagle Rays can be found. The caves are quite interesting.

text.description1: This site is a shallow and narrow channel with great coral life with a few coral blocks that act as cleaning stations for fish and larger marine animals.
text.description2: Manta rays at the cleaning stations, garden eels all over the sandy bottom, and nice corals. Look under the coral blocks to see resting rays and sharks.

text.description1: Dive site located on the outer reef (East Side). Usually a drift dive following the contour of the reef. If the current is slow, more time can be spent exploring the rocks (cleaning station).
text.description2: Fish life is amazing around the rocks. Grey reefsharks can be seen cleaning, Whitetip reefsharks laying on the sea floor or sleeping inside crevices in the rocks, and diverse fish life.

text.description1: It is a drift dive done along the outer reef. Depending on the speed and direction of the current, the dive can be ended or started at Kassanfaru Corner.
text.description2: A variety of pelagic life can be spotted while drifting along with the current including different types of sharks and rays, and schools of fishes.

text.description1: This reef is located inside the channel at the northeast of North Male Atoll and offers some interesting overhangs and some swim-throughs for those who enjoy putting their buoyancy skills to use.
text.description2: A great spot for enjoying different reef fish species, searching for octopus, lobster, nudibranch. Enjoy the coral and marine life found in the overhangs.

text.description1: Muthafushi Thila is a small pinnacle dive site. This site is great for avid photographers and those who enjoy diving slow and looking around to discover all the life this reef has to offer.
text.description2: This dive site is covered in yellow net coral, hard corals, and anemones. The pinnacle is teeming with small reef fish and is also a great refuge for sea turtles.

text.description1: Maalhos Manta point is our very own Manta Ray cleaning station on the island reef. It is a bit of a swim away and we usually take a boat out there to make it a bit more comfortable.
text.description2: Manta Rays can be seen between April and November. Whale Sharks also do pop up from time to time. We do like to snorkel all the way to this spot and back from time to time.

text.description1: Maalhos House Reef is easily accessible from the beach. The reef is right off the shore, and starts at a few meters and drops off. There are several small overhangs all over. It is possible to do a nice, long and relaxed dive here.
text.description2: Marine life is diverse as the house reef gets favorable currents. Turtles, moray eels, reef sharks, and rays are seen. Fish life is very good.

text.description1: Dharavandhoo Thila orients itself on a north, slightly northwestern to south, slightly southeastern axis, with its shallow end being on the south, coming up to a rooftop at around 6 meters. You’ve got a good 20-30 meters of oval-shaped reef top, which slopes gently down to a sandy bottom a bit over 20m.
text.description2: Dharavandhoo Thila is a great spot for macro lovers and photographers, there is also a manta ray cleaning station during the Southwest monsoon, between May and November.

text.description1: Please note: This is a snorkeling only site! Hanifaru Bay is the most famous manta ray feeding and breeding ground in the Maldives and the largest known in the world! Don’t miss out on this fantastic spot between May and November.
text.description2: Manta rays and whale sharks can be found here from May to November. The surrounding reef is also full of other marine life such as white-tip reef sharks, green turtles, sweetlips, etc.

text.description1: Anga Faru translates to Mouth Reef in the local language, is a big reef with a lagoon and sand bank enclosed. The slope is fairly steep in some areas and there are multiple overhangs.
text.description2: All sorts of marine life can be seen while drifting along the reef. Turtles, Manta Rays, Eagle Rays and Sharks can be seenThe over hangs are full of soft coral, mainly blue soft coral.

text.description1: Maavaru Thila is made up of 2 different thilas (pinnacles) a deeper one to start the dive on and a shallower thila that is perfect to finish the dive on.
text.description2: The beauty of this site is the amount of soft corals covering both thilas, the abundance of fish life, and the chance to spot a green sea turtle or two.

text.description1: A pleasant reef to snorkel or dive to explore. A vertical hole in the reef creates a blue hole like swim through allows scuba divers to descend down and exit from a cave at the bottom.
text.description2: Guitar sharks and rays can be seen here. Turtles cruise by and general fish life is quite good. Nice spot for a leisurely dive.

text.description1: This site gets its name from the many canyons and overhangs that you can find between 12 and 30 meters. These crevices make great shelter for the nearby marine life. The coral growth here starts at around 10 meters. This site is suitable for all levels, although there can be strong currents.
text.description2: Fares Canyons offers the diver very diverse marine life in large schools, a great spot for avid underwater photographers.

text.description1: Alighaa Beyru Edge isn’t only located at a channel corner; the dive site actually sits directly at the south western corner of Lhaviyani Atoll. Drive time from Le Meridien Maldives is 35 minutes. The highlight of this dive site is surely the very impressive oceanic edge. Best dived on a nice south western current.
text.description2: We can find some turtles on the main reef which make the trip one to matter. Also expect to encounter grey reef sharks as well as sleeping rays.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: Alighaa Beyru Faru is located about 40 minutes south west of Le Meridien Maldives. As with most farus, it’s a relatively easy drift dive along a beautiful coral covered reef. The top is at 5 meters and then slopes down to 30 meters and beyond (100 meters plus)
text.description2: At various depths you will find overhangs (with stingrays). Keep an eye out for grey reef sharks cruising along the reef as well as napoleon wrasses and of course tuna.

text.description1: Miyaru is the Dhivehi (Maldivian) word for shark. Gaa means as much as “Block“ in the local language. Putting both parts together creates the perfect description of this place. To be more precise “Nurse Shark Block“ would hit the nail on its head...
text.description2: With a depth level of 2 to 7 meters, this block is the ideal place to observe the local nurse sharks and stingrays which are cruising around this area. Ideal for diving and snorkeling!

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: One of our best dive sites! Maduvvari Dhekunu Kann is located on a channel corner west of Le Meridien Maldives. A 25-minute boat ride takes us to this prime dive spot, which is suitable for experienced divers who feel comfortable with deep dives in potentially strong currents.
text.description2: There is fish just about everywhere with fusiliers and snappers in massive numbers, as well as schooling sharks, napoleons and all other pelagic.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: A great dive site for shark lovers. Maduvvari Irumathi Kann is located on a channel corner towards the west of Le Meridien and it requires only a 25-minute boat ride to get there. We start the dive on the faru (long reef) and drift with the current. The closer to the channel we get the livelier it will become.
text.description2: We usually see grey reef sharks that hunt in the current and feathertail stingrays that either sleep or can be spotted when swimming past.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: Halaaku Thari Thila lies a 10-minute ride to the north. The name translates into “broken star thila” and this is exactly what the topography looks like. Overall, the dive site offers a beautiful underwater landscape including an almost vertical wall with lots of healthy hard corals around.
text.description2: Stingrays, eagle rays, anemone fish and batfish are often seen here and both humpback and blue line snappers make the dive a very colorful and also “fishy” experience.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: Gaa Vehtunu Thila translates into “fallen stone” reef. The fallen stone actually describes a reef structure west of the main reef consists of a big mushroom coral block at 19 meters depth. The main thila has a small top reef at 5 meters from where it drops gradually to about 20 meters.
text.description2: Turtles, stingrays, areas full of glassfish on the northern part of the dive site while the south is the territory for both blue line and humpback snappers.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: This beautiful thila is located south west of Le Meridien Maldives. The top of the reef is at about 5 - 8 meters, going down to around 30 meters. Overall, Maduvvari Haa is teaming with life. In the South west is a nice overhang and the north east you’ll find a beautiful coral garden mainly consisting of hard coral
text.description2: We will find dogtooth tuna and eagle rays and a large group of schooling blue line snappers as well as quite a few groupers. Check underneath rocks and corals for some lobsters.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: The dive at Thin Sehli starts fairly shallow at around 5 meters then gradually drops down to 25 meters on all sides. The dive site features some really nice coral blocks and is home to several cleaning stations where cleaning wrasses are waiting for larger fish to come by to get “cleaned”.
text.description2: Thin Sehli Thila on a lucky day is a good place to come eye to eye with the elusive ornate eagle ray who has been spotted here a few times already. We also often see nurse sharks.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: The reef starts at about 5 meters, where you’ll find a few rocks and hard coral blocks. Make sure to have a look underneath the various blocks to spot some lobsters. The main thila drops to about 25 to 30 meters and features some very nice coral gardens in the north east that are teeming with life.
text.description2: Tropical reef fish, nudibranches and glass fish are common to appear in front of the divers’ mask. Sleeping sting rays and usually large green turtles.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: The house reef at Thilamaafushi is located at the north of the island. It is sheltered from the elements and therefore accessible for practically the entire year for both divers and snorkelers alike. It offers four different dive sites and includes a thila, which is a typical Maldivian reef structure.
text.description2: The house reef is great for macro diving as well as some bigger surprise such as passing mantas. You will find many sleeping rays and nurse sharks on sandy patches.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: Located 30 minutes west of Le Meridien, the dive site is close to the small island of Varihuraa. We start the dive on the reef at a depth in between 8 and 10 meters. Conducted as a drift dive, we simply hang in the current and see how far we can get.
text.description2: On the channel corner itself we often find large groups of rainbow runners, jackfish and also schooling barracuda. Stingrays are also often spotted.

text.description1: Ahga Giri is a small reef with its reeftop at 5 meters. The place is famous for its resident nurse sharks which grow quite big at the place. A stunning experience without any comparison!
text.description2: Despite limited coral life the place is a must for avid divers. Better nurse shark encounters are barely possible...

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: A five-minute boat ride to the east take us to the neighboring local island Olhuvelifsuhi. The shallows are covered in sand which is why we also call this dive site “the milky sand reef”.
text.description2: Feathertails, marble rays, jenkins rays and their brothers and sisters can be seen resting in the sand during the day. During the season even mantas frequent this reef.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: Olhuveli Medhu Faru is located 5 minutes to the east of Le Meridien Maldives. The reef structure is very unique. It starts from 2 meters and connects into separate reefs and small thilas all the way down to 30 meters. It is spread very wide and gives endless possibilities how to dive the area.
text.description2: Healthy hard corals and many different kinds of stingrays are home here. Both hawksbill and green turtles are abundant. Dragon heads have also been found here.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: About a 15-minute boat ride to the north west of Le Meridien we find the small Talabo Thila. Talabo is Divehi for “bald person” because of the lack of beautiful corals. The dive starts at about 5 meters and then drops down to a sandy bottom at around 20 – 25 meters where we can often find rare porcupine stingrays
text.description2: Some beautiful blocks. Abundant fish life, sleeping nurse sharks and various sting rays in the sand.

text.description1: This long shallow channel dive is located in the northeast of Laamu atoll. The drop off starts at around 16 meters. This dive site is only for advanced or expert divers as the currents can be very strong.
text.description2: This is the site for large pelagic lovers. Here you will see sharks in abundance, eagle rays, schools of tuna and jack fish, sail fish and on the odd occasion schooling hammerheads.

text.description1: Candice Thila is a beautiful small reef with it’s reef top around 5m and its bottom at around 30 meters. It is located 15 boat minutes north of Le Meridien Maldives
text.description2: The Thila has a beautiful top reef with healthy hard coral life in all colors. The resident batfishes make sure no one gets bored... Schooling fishes all around!

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: Lhohi Dekunu Kann is located north west of Le Meridien Maldives. It requires a 35-minute boat ride to get there and jump into the blue and warm waters surrounding the lovely reef. We conduct the dive as a drift dive and it is therefore suitable for divers of all levels.
text.description2: Lhohi Corner is famous for the green turtles. Expect sharks, rays, fusiliers, rainbow runners, snappers, surgeonfish and many other tropical reef fish.

text.description1: nice drift dive first in a small bay and later on a steep wall. In the bay, sloping from 4 to 22m to then have a small dropoff. With a bit of luck you can see the wonderful manta rays passing by here from January to April.
text.description2: huge groupers, perch, stingrays, napoleons, snails, lots of moray eels, shrimps, lobsters with colorful corals and a good chance of mantas from January to April

text.description1: This dive can be started along the reef wall or in the blue depending on the current. Here the bottom off the channel and “drop off“ is at 18 meters. This dive site can have strong current.
text.description2: Look in the overhangs to find schools of snapper or soldierfish taking shelter. Other marine life includes stingrays, white tip and grey reef sharks, barracuda, eagle rays, and much more!

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: The dive site itself actually consists of two dive sites that are divided by a sandy plateau at 8 meters. South of the plateau we can find a large lagoon with an average depth of about 12 meters. On the other side towards the north and north west a sloping and long reef called faru ranges from 10 to 30 meters.
text.description2: Nice corals, mantas during the season, a lot of glass fish blocks, turtles, shrimps, moray eels and many other tropical reef fish.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: A 10-minute boat ride to the north and we arrive at Boava Thila. Located north of Le Meridien and in the inside atoll, the dive site is suitable for beginners and experienced divers alike. The reef features large patches with beautiful black coral .
text.description2: It is a great spot to find turtles. Small cracks and overhangs are home to lobsters, moray eels and stone fish.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: A nice and easy site 20 minutes to the north east of Le Meridien Maldives. A top reef with healthy hard coral gardens at about 5 meters. he dive site reaches a depth of a maximum of 25 meters and features a large and very nice coral block in the north east at approximately 20 meters depth.
text.description2: You’ll have the joys of schooling blue line snappers as well as other colorful reef fish such as surgeon fish, angel fish and many damsels.
