text.description1: This is a very wide Kandu, the reef top in the channel is about 12 to 14 meters deep and the corals here are in good condition, the edge drops down into the deep ocean and you can float in the blue along the wall.
text.description2: Schools of snapper, Fuselier, Dogtooth Tuna, Jack, Giant Travellie, Groupers and many more are seen and all the variations of Maldives fish.

text.description1: This is a small thila 80m long and 70m wide in the middle of a channel which promises a lot of currents. Due to the current, this dive site should be dived by experienced divers only, or those who are willing to learn! Smart diving in the current’s shade required or the right place to be shown by an experienced instructor.
text.description2: Eagle rays, nurse sharks, scorpionfish, real stonefish, mackerel, large moray eels, honeycomb moray eels, shrimp, and longnose hawkfish.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: Salleydhoo Thila is another lovely dive site located about a 15-minute boat ride to the north of Le Meridien Maldives. Salleydhoo Thila has a very interesting topography. The southern part of the dive site doesn’t have the usual round-ish shape, but we find two tongues here that reach a depth of 20 – 22 meters.
text.description2: The highlight on these tongues are the thousands of glassfish that live here. On the thila itself we usually see an abundance of marine life such as a great variety of surgeonfish

text.description1: Maamunagaa Giri is like an isosceles triangle and can only be approached in good weather. The south side lies on the deep channel between Baa and Raa Atoll. Here, and on the northwest side, you can often see gray reef sharks and a beautiful school of jackfish. Macro life lies in the small overhangs and holes.
text.description2: Gray reef sharks, stingrays, ghost moray eels, many other moray eels, napoleons, butterflyfish, a great school of bannerfish, and sometimes nurse sharks on the reef top.

text.description1: Small Thila directly on the island of Villingilli on the offshore plateau in the direction of the channel between Raa and Baa Atoll. Usually a jump into the blue water east of the Thila above the plateau at the edge for approx. Let drift along 30m towards Thila and then slowly climb up the Thila. Current !!!!
text.description2: Eagle rays, gray reef sharks, giant stingrays, Napoleon, scorpionfish and at the right time manta rays ...

text.description1: If you want to see anemones you have to come to this place,, there is a field with hundreds of anemones where we also can always find turtles. The Giri has approx. a diameter of 120m and is easy to dive around. Some nice small overhangs
text.description2: Clown fish, tunas, mackerel, sometimes deeper gray reef sharks, on the walls many scorpion fish, morays and shrimps

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: Hudhu Thila is a great site for macro diving. Hudhu Thila is located north east of Le Meridien and has a top reef at approximately 5 meters. From there it drops to the bottom at 25 to 30 meters and features some lovely overhangs. Hudhu Thila is a great site for macro diving.
text.description2: Rare pipefish which are in the same family as seahorses can be found as well as scorpion fish and nudibranches. Lobsters, octopus and lion fish and various kinds of anemone fish.

text.description1: This dive site is a must for all experienced divers. The small main block, only about 80m round, is surrounded by smaller reefs that are almost canyon-like and have holes and arcs to dive through. Due to the location, this dive is great for deep / nitrox.
text.description2: Grey reef sharks, eagle rays, tunas, mackerel, Napoleon wrasse, nurse sharks, scorpionfish, longnose hawkfish, turtles, stingrays, moray eels, snails, octopus, and an incredible amount of fish!

text.description1: Regardless of whether Thila or the nearby main reef BDT is the best Marco place, which does not mean that there are no big fish;) However, there are occasional “funny currents“ which are no problem with a guide who knows his way around! After the small Thila, simply hold the current right / left shoulder and drift
text.description2: Ghost morays and at least 8 other species, skorpion fish, small yellow box fish, shrimp,eagle rays, stingrays, gray reef sharks. Mantas possible at the right time of year

text.description1: Because of its current, BKT is reserved for experienced divers or is dived in times of low current. Not far from BBT, the rock rises to a depth of 16m. The south side has a nice plateau at 25m and then drops off steeply to 40m. Cleaning station for gray reef sharks!
text.description2: Gray reef sharks, rarely also Silvertip !, eagle rays, a lot of small items and at the right time mantas or mobulas possible.

text.description1: 300m long and 80m wide, this site is a must-dive reef. On the west side, the reef falls slowly from 14 to 18m, then steeply to 30m. In front, there is a large block starting at 28m. With a little bit of luck, you will see nurse sharks here. The southwest side is crisscrossed with beautiful colorful overhangs. Current!!
text.description2: Large groupers, Napoleon wrasse, grey reef sharks, turtles, lobsters, long-nosed hawkfish, and small shrimp. Beautiful soft corals and a great gorgonian field!

text.description1: BBT is a dive site that you can dive every day and each time you“ii find different conditions and creatures. The reef top starts at 5m, at 8 / 9m it drops down to 30m. There are some small overhangs in the western part of the Thila which are partly overgrown with soft corals.
text.description2: Gray reef sharks, nurse sharks, eagle rays, hedgehogs / black point / mangroves and normal stingrays. Countless dragon heads, 8/10 different type of morays and lots of crabs and shrimp

text.description1: As the name says it is a deep dive but the top of the thila is about 3 meters. Great dive for beginners and advance divers alike. Wall, overhang and large boulders, swarming with schools of fish.
text.description2: Eagle rays, white tip reef shark are seen here, as schools of parrotfish and Fusilier fish. Also, turtles have been spotted

text.description1: Drift dive along Kudathulhaadhoo Island. Large overhang with soft corals in the west, caves in the middle, and a small bay and the tip in the east is full of fish
text.description2: In the holes and caves nurse sharks, stingrays, huge groupers, scorpionfish. Moray eels outside still the schools with butterflyfish. Now and then eagle rays fly by.

text.description1: The icing on the cake of our thilas is EXTREME! EXTREME CURRENT! EXTREMELY DEEP! therefore only for the experts among our guests. Please do not ask for this place because of its location, we can only approach it under certain conditions. We will talk to you about it if it is possible! Nitrox / Deep
text.description2: Silvertips (rare), gray reef sharks, barracudas, tunas, mackerels, giant lobsters, longnose hawkfish, napoleons, stingrays, eagle rays, and a large school of batfish or barracudas

text.description1: The Kandu is situated Noth-West of the Island Mavaah, the channel Bottom is about 14-16 meters and drops off into the ocean. The coral life is good and abundant fish life.Grey Reef shark, Whitetip Shark, Groupers, Triggerfish etc. When the current is slight all level of divers can participate in the dive.
text.description2: Grey Reef Shark. White Tip Reef Shark. Eagle Ray. Schools of Fuselier and Snappers are common Good Coral live, Black Coral trees.

text.description1: Great challenging reef that consists of 2 thilas. The eastern Thila is not that big and is circled in 25 to 30 minutes then you fly about. 120m to the 2nd thila. Here it goes down again to look for a frogfish. Between November and April mantas and mobulas possible.
text.description2: Frogfish, Longnose hawkfish, Napoleon, eagle rays, jackfish, scorpionfish, stonefish, snails, and between November and April manta rays and mobulas possible

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: It takes us 55 minutes by boat to get there from Le Meridien. The dive site is also a super beautiful macro haven. The dive at Ihi starts at shallow depth of 5 to 8 meters. In the north it drops steeply to approximately 25 meters.
text.description2: The dive site is covered in beautiful overhangs where we find amazing macro life such as pipefish and nudibranches. Soldierfish, lobsters and lionfish are also abundant

text.description1: Drift dive with the current flowing from the western tip of Kinohlas along the north side towards the small Thila. Lots of fish on the top of the reef, some really nice little overhangs deeper. Experienced divers dive to the thila, beginners stay over the overhangs and slowly ascend the Sandy Slope
text.description2: stingrays, porcupine rays (rare), eagle rays, and whitetip reef sharks, huge groupers and other large perch, turtles, lots of fish and macro on the reef top

text.description1: A small reef with many different types of colorful coral. The reef roof is at a height of 6m and has a diameter of approx. 20m, at a depth of 25m it should be approx. 50m. On the west side an overhang with soft corals, further deeper a gap with giant moray eels and cleaner shrimp.
text.description2: Giant moray eels, shrimp, Napoleon, grouper, various snails, scorpionfish, stonefish, octopus with a little luck eagle rays

text.description1: A simple, mostly calm dive site.Very suitable for the first boat dive since the beginning lighter sandy bottom.Big blocs with schooling fish of different species are here encountered. The reef falls on very slowly from 2m down to about 11m and then aplateau run out at a depth of 20-24m.
text.description2: Giant box fish, Morays, Anemones,Stone fish, Scorpion fish, Lobsters and many different kinds of shrimps and crabs. Turtles, Stingrays, Eagle rays and sometimes Mantas

text.description1: Smaller thila that is easy to circle around when simple current conditions prevail. The reef top starts at 7m with small blocks. To the east and north, it does not drop so steeply to 25m. In the west and south a little steeper up to 35m. In the south-west are beautiful small. Overhangs.
text.description2: Small and big come together. Eagle rays, nurse shark, Napoleon, dragon head, various snails, shrimps, glassfish, small boxfish and with a lot of luck guitar rays

text.description1: ADT is a deep thila in front off the island of Aarah. With a current from the west, we start on the gently sloping part of the lagoon in the south-west. We drift in a deep of 22m to the first small block and from there to the thila. If the current is not too strong, the dive can be ended at the main reef
text.description2: Gray reef sharks. Barracudas, Napoleon, big groupers, glass fish and eagle rays but also giant morays and macros stuff like shrimp and snails on the Thila roof

text.description1: Great drift dive over several large blocks and small thilas. Due to distances of 80m and currents more demanding and for experienced divers or divers willing to learn. Nice overhangs and arches in the deeper area, Deep / Nitrox has the best combination. Depending on the current, you can go diving on the house reef
text.description2: Stingrays, nurse sharks, lionfish, scorpionfish, moray eels, small yellow boxfish, hunting tunas and mackerel, snails, and in summer on the western block sometimes mantas (July / Aug)

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: Just insane! That exclamation best describes Nemo Thila which is located 60 minutes to the north of Le Meridien. The dive site will blow your mind and not surprisingly, it is located inside a national park. Stunning colors and more juvenile fish and small sardines than you could ever imagine live here.
text.description2: Leopard sharks, grey reef sharks, lion fish, lobsters, mantis shrimp, moray eels and octopus. Also a lot of blue line snappers and many anemones.

text.description1: This is a drift dive suitable for all levels. Beginners drift past the upper overhangs at 10-15m, while the more experienced divers head deeper at 25m to take a look at the overhangs there. The relatively steep reef is fully covered with soft coral when there is a current. Nitrox / Deep specialties recommended.
text.description2: Eagle rays, zackis, gray reef sharks, stingrays, and nurse sharks, plus lots of lobsters and some snails and crabs. There is also lots of colorful soft corals.

text.description1: DivePoint MEP makes here the night dives and sometimes also Current Specialty Dives. The reef goes down from 3-4m to 30m. Some nice Blocks a bit higher are full of clownfish and in the night you will find often a lot of lobsters and shrimps. But its not always possible to dive here. The current can be extreme!!
text.description2: under the jetty full of fish, in the reef different type of moray eels and a nice variation of shrimps and lobsters give you a really interesting night dive.

text.description1: Simple but beautiful dive that starts slowly at 5m in a bay and then dives at 15-20m on the right shoulder with a current from west to east. Some small holes in the wall. There you can find a lot of macro but also scorpionfish and the longnose hawkfish in the coral bushes. In the blue water Napoleon and eagle rays
text.description2: Napoleon, eagle rays on the reef roof a lot of fish, scorpionfish, stonefish, nurse sharks in the small blocks and with a little luck also a large porcupine ray

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: The dive at Dhihfushimaadhoo Beyru is usually a gentle drift dive towards a channel or vice versa. Located on the outside reef you can expect great visibility and very nice hard corals. The lagoon is connected to the open ocean and offers the perfect breeding and nursing grounds for all types of fish.
text.description2: At depth we find some large and very interesting coral blocks that act like a magnet for tropical reef fish. Watch out for eagle rays that cruise the reef, and nurse sharks in the sand.

text.description1: Wonderful drift dive in a frenzy of colors. This reef is like an open subway tunnel cut on the side. Soft corals in many different colors hang everywhere in the tunnel. In the middle of the canal, there are coral blocks with a good chance of gray reef shark (when there’s current). The perfect place for a current specialty!
text.description2: Small stuff like scorpionfish and snails but also big life like groupers, Napoleon wrasse, eagle rays, stingrays, and at the right time, mantas and mobulas.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: Faadhoo Kandu is one of the two magnificent channels located north east of Le Meridien Maldives. The potential strong current is not for the faint hearted and a crossing is only possible on a mild current since the bottom is too deep to be able to hide from it.
text.description2: Channel lovers will find here what the Maldives are famous for: Sharks, napoleons, jack fish, stingrays, eagle rays, dogtooth tuna, bluefin tuna, bonitos, trevally as well as nice coral

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: Imagine a wall! A real drop off that doesn’t stop dropping! A reef that disappears into the blue! Do you have the picture in front of your inner eye? Then you are right at Faadhoo Beyru, one of the best dive sites we have on offer in the proximity of Le Meridien Maldives.
text.description2: The dive site itself is quite diverse. We can see lobsters, sweetlips, schooling snappers, many different types of schooling jackfish as well as turtles. Also expect a curious batfish.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: A site not to be missed by the experienced diver. With the right current Meyyafushi Kandu is a great channel to cross and experience what so many people come to the Maldives for. Starting from either one of the corners the actual swim only takes about 20 minutes.
text.description2: Imagine schooling jack’s and trevallies, napoleon fish swimming in between and then the tunas that appear almost clumsy in between all of those gracious predators.

elements.copyright: Sub Oceanic @ Le Méridien Maldives, 00000 Malé

text.description1: We find this gem of a dive site after a 50 minutes boat ride to the north east. The dive site offers a wide variety of reef structures. You can experience a great sandy plateau with several cleaning stations and a wall with beautiful overhangs and soft corals during the same dive.
text.description2: Mantas frequent the reef during the season and you can see all types of stingrays, eagle rays, tunas, nurse sharks, curious batfish and turtles all year round.

text.description1: An approximately 600m long drift dive in a frenzy of colors that is dived in different levels. however, it is also a place where things really get down to business every now and then! The current drive you in 6 minutes; ) from beginning to end. Therefore flow specialty recommended!
text.description2: Nurse sharks, whitetip reef sharks, stingrays, napoleons, turtles, big groupers, manta rays (NOV-APRIL) many beautiful soft corals, snails, shrimp and much more

text.description1: The reef top has something of a lunar landscape, despite or precisely because of this it is often a very special dive. The northern side often serves as a starting point when the current is draining from a steep wall over a sandy plateau to a normal slope. Manta rays between the end of September and November
text.description2: Whitetip reef shark, turtles, napoleons, huge groupers and other perches, batfish, honey comb moray eels, shrimp, crabs and snails. September-November manta rays

text.description1: After a 35min boat ride we arrive on Kottefaru Bodu Thila. From July to November you can have wonderful Manta dives and the best on it, its easy diving, also with current you can easy see that amazing animals.
text.description2: On the cleaning blocks, you will find sweetlips and :) Mantas from July to November, in front of the west corner you go a bit deeper to see the grey reef sharks

text.description1: A very nice drift dive over several hundred meters along the island of Kottefaru. The top reef is made of hard corals that drop from 4 to 8m, sloping down to 15m, then a wall that drops far more than 30m. On the top reef between June and November the site becomes a cleaning station for mantas.
text.description2: A lot of macro, lots of fish, Napoleon wrasse, turtles, gray reef sharks, silvertips, manta rays, and very rarely hammerheads! It’s a jackpot!!!

text.description1: Great thila with many small overhangs that often serve as shelter for rays, nurse sharks and turtles. Soft corals and extremely many anemones !! Due to its location in a canal, a current must always be expected. We, therefore, recommend having experience with currents or a * special * dive.
text.description2: Grey reef sharks, stingrays, eagle rays, turtles, a big school of jackfish and between Juli and November a good chance to see Mantas on the top reef or the beautiful block in the north.

text.description1: This fantastic pinnacle gets its name from a blanket of anemones covering the top of the reef. There are 2 large overhangs on opposite sides of the thila full of interesting corals and glass fish.
text.description2: Manta rays can be encountered from May to December as they come here to get clean. This site has it all with possible sightings of sharks, rays, and all the tropical fish you can imagine.

text.description1: This spectacular wall site, located in the Southeast of Raa Atoll, makes for an interesting drift dive, starting at around 12m and dropping down to over 80m in depth!
text.description2: This site is special for its bright pink fire coral covering the wall at around 18 meters. There are also a few manta ray cleaning stations along the reef edge.

Sea Explorers Associates Pvt. Ltd., 20008 Male

text.description1: A shallow dive site good for Beginners and Re activate dives, Coral boulders with patches of fine white sand. Mainly 12 meters deep but possible to get deeper, little to no current on this spot.
text.description2: Boulder corals, branching corals, turtles, stingray and large variety of fish, triggerfish Snappers etc.

text.description1: From November / December to the beginning of May one of the best manta spots in the Maldives! Also suitable for beginners! But not only mantas are sighted here. Lots of pelagic delicacies can be discovered with a bit of luck. Can have a stronger current, but easy to dive.
text.description2: Mantas, eagle rays, marble/mangroves, and normal stingrays, white tip and gray reef sharks, lots of Napoleons, tunas, and in the blue water sometimes a Silvertip or even a whale shark.

text.description1: This pinnacle is located in the northeast channel of Lhaviyani Atoll. You can find a large plateau covered in coral blocks that act as cleaning stations for the manta rays during the southwest monsoon.
text.description2: This channel is not only special for mantas but has also great fish life. Here you can spot large schools of fish, tropical reef fish, and sharks.

text.description1: This is on the inside reef fringe near Hedha, about 40 minutes sailing from Rahaa Resort. Snorkelers will also enjoy this reef, that is amazing well covered with live corals.Very easy in the west-east monsoon,
text.description2: Mainly a dive site for the corals and landscape but has good fish life as well, turtles and eagle rays are observed here.

text.description1: This beautiful thila is about 40 minutes sailing from Rahaa Resort, the fish life is abundant and the corals are beautiful and in a large variation. The site is for all levels of divers.
text.description2: Schools of fusiliers, sweetlips, snappers, groupers and triggerfishes. Shark and Turtle are seen here too.

text.description1: More of a typical Maldivian manta site i.e. a block on a sandy area and manta rays that may or may not use the block as a cleaning station. The sloping reef is between 5 and 15m guarded and offers many small fish a home. On the huge sandy area at 20m we also find stingrays.
text.description2: Eagle rays, stingrays, napoleon, scorpion fish, moray eels, shrimps and at the right time manta rays.

text.description1: The name says it all, Boulders around from 5 to 24 meters deep, A dive for all levels, about 35 minutes from Rahaa ResortSnorkelers will also enjoy this site
text.description2: This site has a lot of young fish and fry but also you will see the Fuselier, snappers, pufferfish, We can also see stingrays resting on the sand.

text.description1: An approximately 200m long thila in the channel between Kottefaru and Vandhoo where we dive the north side. Here it goes down in steps down to 45-50m. The overhangs are nicely covered with soft corals. In the blue water, the grays pull their lanes. With beginners, we try to find calm conditions.
text.description2: Gray reef sharks, eagles and stingrays, large groupers, turtles, nurse sharks, scorpionfish, shrimp, and various types of moray eels.

text.description1: This channel dive site is in the north of Lhaviyani Atoll. Inside the channel is a tongue-shaped reef with plateau reef, slopes, walls, and drop-offs.
text.description2: This site is great for spotting huge stingrays as well as eagle rays, tuna, and schools of jack fish.

text.description1: A very nice drift dive over several hundred meters along the island of Vandhoo. The top reef made of hard corals drops from 4 to approx. 8m, sloping down to 15m, then a 250m long wall that drops to over 30m +. On the TOP reef, between June and November, is a cleaning station for Mantas.
text.description2: Many fish, Napoleons, turtles, gray reef sharks, Silvertips, manta rays, snails, and vortex worms, plus lots of macro life on the reef top and on the sloping slope.

text.description1: This great dive site is characterized by a wonderful underwater landscape in the south. The top reef starts at about 3m and drops to about 10m.Then the wall is criss-crossed with beautiful overhangs that can be dived to a depth of 30m. Upstream a small Thila that comes from 33 to 18m, Nitrox and deep specialty!
text.description2: A wonder bag from small shrimps to a lot of fish, napoleons, gray reef sharks, dolphins to manta rays - everything is possible

elements.copyright: Sea Explorers Associates Pvt. Ltd., 20008 Male

text.description1: This Thila starts at about 8-9 meters and than falls down to 30+ meters on the south there is a big free standing Boulder from 16 meters down to 32 meters this Boulder is fully grown with Corals and a big black coral tree
text.description2: Black Coral, trevallies, fusilier fish, box fish, branching corals, sponges, eagle rays, Tiger Cowry shells.

text.description1: You should have some experience for this TOP dive site! The reef top starts at 15m! and is a block about 80x70m around it are large blocks full of fish and soft corals. There is a nice little canyon and small breakthroughs! NITROX and DEEP Specialty desirable !!
text.description2: Grey reef sharks, nurse sharks, eagle rays, stingrays, turtles, scorpionfish but also tinny yellow boxfish and slugs

text.description1: This Thila is about 25 minutes from Rahaa, The top starts at 3-4 meters deep and decent to about 28meter, South East of the thila is a sloping coral plateau, Coral block, black coral trees, groupers and fusilier etc.
text.description2: Turtle, Fusilier, groupers, surgeon fish, snappers, black tip reef shark, great coral life, massifs as well as carpet and branching corals

text.description1: Site is about 25 minutes from Rahaa Resort. It is ideal for your fresh-up dive and check out after a long stay away from diving. The depth is max 24m, abundant coral life.
text.description2: We see turtle, rays, parrotfish, fusilier fish, snappers. The coral is very good and the variety is amazing. Massive corals, branching corals and sea fans

text.description1: This Thila starts at 3 meters depth and has beautiful coral live. Can be reached from Rahaa Resort in approx.. 35 minutes. The dive site is suitable for all levels of divers .
text.description2: Beside the large variety of coral there are groupers, fusilier fish, surgeon fish and many other variety of fish.

text.description1: The Turtle Caves are not so much caves as very large overhangs along the reef wall. This dive site is located in the North of Lhaviyani Atoll next to the resort island of Kuredu.
text.description2: Turtles, turtles, turtles! This is the site for turtle lovers, with the friendliest green sea turtles you will ever meet.

text.description1: Located South of You&Me Resort, close to Kadholhudhoo Island in the Channel. Distance by boat is 45min ride. It’s an underwater pinnacle where the top of the Giri starts from 6 to 7m dropping down to 30m. On the southern side of the Giri there are a couple of big coral blocks, where big encounters are possible.
text.description2: School of batfishes, snappers, sweetlips, napoleonwrasse, lobster, eagle rays, grey reef sharks, hawksbill turtle.

text.description1: this beautiful reef is located on south eat side of You&Me and the boat navigation time is 20min. this is a reef like a gentle slop with a lot off small stuff
text.description2: nudibranchs, turtles, tunas, lion fishes and of course full of fishes with beautiful corals in any depth.

text.description1: We can reach Thilin Faru in 20min by boat. Top reef lays at 10mt with a coral slope to 15mt and then to 30mt. On the corner a sandy area surrounded by coral blocks with a Manta cleaning station.
text.description2: Easy to encounter grey reef sharks, eagle rays, sting rays, schools of snappers and, in the right season, manta rays.

text.description1: this beautiful dive site is located on south east side of You&Me and the boat navigation time is 35min. top reef start from 3m and this is the house reef of koli kuredhdhoo
text.description2: reef lobsters, bannerfishes, nudibranchs, turtles, flat warms, nurse sharks and full of other common fishes.

text.description1: located on southern side of You&Me and the navigation time is 25min. Gentle slope with hard corals and some coral blocks on the sand bottom on 18m.
text.description2: Schools of blue stripped snappers, lobsters, sting rays, snappers, turtles and the manta season reef mantas are possible to see.

text.description1: this thila is located on north side of You&Me and the boat navigation time 15m. this thila is like a round and a gentle slop thila and top reef starts from 2m.
text.description2: moray eels, fusiliers, octopus, Napoleon, snappers, blue fin trevally and the seasonal littlie bait fishes.

text.description1: Very nice gentle slope reef and with some overhangs it starts from 8m till 20m. This dive site is located on southern side of You&Me and the navigation time is around 18min.
text.description2: Mantas season is possible to see the reef mantas, sting rays, lobsters, nurse sharks and schools of bluestripe snappers.

text.description1: Amazing shallow dive with full of hard corals and nice slope with finest clear sandy bottom.. located on northeast corner of the sand bank reef....
text.description2: blue stripe snappers, guitarfish, sting rays, red snappers, midnight snappers, eagle rays and full of garden eels.

text.description1: This especial giri is located on north side of You&Me and the boat navigation time is 8minutes. Top reef is in 1m and the reef bottom is 25m with macro stuff.
text.description2: Different kind of nudibranchs, flat worms, lionfishes, moray eels, snappers, octopus and good spot for night dive.

text.description1: Located on north side of You&Me and the boat navigation time is 10min. Easy and relaxed dive site with macro stuff and healthy coral life. Top reef start from 2m and the reef bottom is 20m.
text.description2: Different nudibranchs, schools of snappers, lion fishes and in the right season possible to see the reef mantas.

text.description1: Deep thila starting at 18m deep going down to 30m. Good dive site for advanced divers, ideally with Nitrox certification. The thila looks like a broken rock separated in many blocks.
text.description2: Big school of fusiliers, blue stripped snappers, eagle rays, gray reef sharks, guitar sharks, turtle and lot of anemone.

text.description1: Wall with amazing hard coral coverage. This dive site is perfect for beginners as well as advanced divers who like to find some small creatures.
text.description2: Acrapora corals. Big school of blue-lined snappers. Octopus. Yellow box fish. Gray reef sharks. Eagle rays. During manta season it is possible to see manta swimming along the reef.

text.description1: this round channel thila is located on the eat side of You&Me and the end of Raa Atoll from the east side. top reef starts from 5m till the 35m.
text.description2: napoleons, gray reef sharks, barracudas, eagle rays, this is a very good dive site for experience divers

text.description1: Madi gaa is divided on two manta cleaning stations, the shallow cleaning station is 13m and the deep cleaning station is 20m. this is a very famous manta cleaning station at uthuru maafaru (You&Me) north corner. boat navigation time is 25min.
text.description2: Giant reef mantas, eagle rays, oriental sweet lips, snappers, nurse sharks, silver jacks and schools of fusiliers.

text.description1: Located north of You&Me Resort at a distance of 20min by boat. Top reef lays at 10mt with a gentle slope dropping to 30mt. On the corner there are a couple of cleaning stations where, from December till April, is possible to encounter Manta Rays.
text.description2: Here is possible to see grey reef sharks, eagle rays, sting rays, big schools of snappers and sweetlips, and, in the right season, Manta Rays.

text.description1: Reacheable in 25min by boat located in the southern side of Fuggiri Island, top reef lays at 10mt depth dropping down straight to 35mt. Between 12 and 18mt many overhangs display beautiful soft corals. At a depth between 25 and 30mt big coral blocks hiding amazing marine life.
text.description2: Colorful soft corals in the overhangs, nudibranches, scorpion fishes. Easy to encounter grey reef sharks, eagle rays and big tuna fishes.

text.description1: this dive site is located on north east site of You&Me. this dive site is good for two way dive and the reef from starts 1m and some areas of the reef is like a wall.
text.description2: napoleons, lot of jack fishes, and a very good spot for macro. this dive site is good specially macro

text.description1: Glass fish cove is a reef where we can find many different overhangs populated by many different kind of marine life species. Often we can cross the path of big napoleon wrasse. The highlights of this dive are the schools of glass fish packed inside the overhangs which are often hunted by trevallies.
text.description2: Schools of glass fish, silver jack fish, bluefin trevally, eagle ray, white tip reef shark, napoleon wrasse, spiny lobster, lion fish, moray eal

text.description1: North East side of You&Me Resort, close to Fuggiri Island in the channel. Distance: 35min by boat. The top of thila is 6 to 7m deep dropping down to 30m on the channel side and 20m in the more inner part. Beautiful overhangs can hide stingrays and nursesharks.
text.description2: Grey reef sharks, nursesharks, school of batfish and snappers and, in the right season, also possible to see mantarays. seafans, gorgonians and whip corals are present on this site as well.

text.description1: This dive site is one of the best and most precious thilas / pinnacles in Noonu atoll. It gets its name from the fact that the pinnacles of the reef are stacked to resemble a christmas tree.
text.description2: This reef is great for tiny macro species, such as nudibranchs, shrimp, crabs, and lobste,r as well as some of the larger fish species, like a school of jack fish, sharks, and turtles.

text.description1: Vaadhoo thia is a very famous dive site it is deep and ocean thila middle of the channel. Top reef starts in 10m and the bottom goes down to 40m with beautiful corals.
text.description2: Grey reef sharks, hammerhead sharks, napoleons, eagle rays, snappers, tunas, turtles and different type of trevallies.

text.description1: Orimas Thila is a deep thila dive site with the top of the thila at approx. 20m. This site is also known as Shark Point due to the sharks that hang around in this area. If the current is strong and you may need to hook into or hold onto the rocks to stay up current with the fish life.
text.description2: With good current, you can see schooling grey reef sharks circling around as well as schools of fish and a group of batfish.

text.description1: Loley Thila is a pinnacle dive site located in the south of Shaviyani Atoll. This site is best reached by liveaboard as there are not so many tourist islands here.
text.description2: This site is famous for its schooling grey reef sharks, you can also find schools of fish, red-toothed triggerfish, scorpionfish and other macro life on the thila itself.

text.description1: This thila / pinnacle is located in the south of Shaviyani atoll and due to the lack of tourism, with very few guesthouses or resorts in this area, this site is best reached by liveaboard.
text.description2: This site is popular for its amazing fish life; if you ever fancied being submerged into a bowl of living fish soup, this is the place for you!

text.description1: Naalaahuraa Thila is one of our best dive sites, located in a channel and is therefore prone to stronger currents. That combined with its depth makes it a dive site for advanced divers. The reef top can be found at 12 meters and the bottom at around 30 meters.
text.description2: Gorgonians and black coral dominate this site. You will also find schooling eagle rays and grey reef sharks dancing in the current as well as schooling fish and stingrays.

text.description1: The dive site is located on the southern side of the island Naalaahuraa and is usually done as a drift dive either starting in the east or west. The reef top starts at 5 meters and goes down to 28 meter. Some beautiful overhangs can be found at around 15 meters and below where you can also find lots of fan corals.
text.description2: Moray eels peek out from their hideouts and anemone fish are plentiful. Don’t forget to have an eye in the blue to spot eagle rays or tuna. Both hunt in the current for their prey.

text.description1: Haru Gaa Thila is located 60 minutes south-east of Fairmont Maldives Sirru Fen Fushi. This thila is a little hidden gem and a seriously nice dive site. The top of the thila starts at about 10 meters and goes down on all sides to around 25 to 27 meters. A very nice dive site that is always worth the trip!
text.description2: Home to a big school of barracudas as well as nurse sharks. Dogtooth tuna circle the reef and to top it all off, there are often sightings of leopard sharks around the thila.

text.description1: This beautiful thila is located south-east of Fairmont Maldives Sirru Fen Fushi. The top of the reef is at about 12 meters, going down to around 30 meters. On the south-east of the thila you will find a beautiful canyon which is often filled with blue striped snappers.
text.description2: Expect a few curious batfish to come and check you out. Make sure to keep an eye out for the dogtooth tunas that circle the thila and hunt in the current.

text.description1: Miyaru Thila is an excellent dive site about 45 minutes south of Fairmont Maldives Sirru Fen Fushi. It is an underwater mount (thila) with the reef top starting at about 10 meters, going down to 30 meters on all sides. You can find beautiful overhangs all over the thila at various depths.
text.description2: Look out for grey reef sharks, eagle rays, and other larger fish in the current and sleeping nurse sharks and rays in the overhangs. Guitarfish might sleep on the sandy patches.

text.description1: Lighthouse Channel has its name because of the little lighthouse that is located in close proximity. The dive site can be reached after a 40 minute boat ride to the south of Fairmont Maldives Sirru Fen Fushi. The dive itself is conducted as a drift dive. We find some extremely “fishy” blocks on the top reef.
text.description2: We find extremely “fishy” blocks on the top reef. Literally thousands of snappers are at home here. The divers’ delight of this site is surely the many eagle rays dancing in the current

text.description1: This thila is located about 30 minutes south of Fairmont Maldives Sirru Fen Fushi. It starts fairly shallow at around 5 meters then gradually drops down to 30+ meters on all sides. The dive usually takes place on the northern side of the thila where most of the action can be found as well as some overhangs.
text.description2: Medhukuburudhoo Thila with the right current is a good place to come eye to eye with the elusive silver tip reef shark and often eagle rays. An excellent site not to be missed.

text.description1: The dive takes place in the south of this very large and pretty reef, which ranges from 10 to 30 meters. In between 20 and 25 meters you will find many lobsters. s. Often a pair or even more are sharing one hole and are a great sight for underwater photographers.
text.description2: The reef is also home to humpback and blue lined snappers as well as the majestic napoleon wrasse. Eagle rays and dogtooth tuna often fly by in the blue so remember to keep an eye out!

text.description1: Medhu Faru is located about 30 minutes south of Fairmont Maldives Sirru Fen Fushi. The reef is attached to an island and starts at around 2-3 meters deep. From there it slopes to 30 meters and beyond. You will find some nice coral life between 20 and 25 meters as well as many beautiful reef fish.
text.description2: Fusiliers are plentiful on the reef and Napoleon wrasse are often spotted. The sandy bottom is the perfect sleeping spot for all kinds of rays found in great abundance in Shaviyani.

text.description1: The reef starts at about 14 meters, where you will find a few rocks and hard coral blocks. Make sure to have a look underneath the various blocks to spot sleeping nurse sharks. The main thila drops steeply to 30 meters and features some nice overhangs that are teeming with life.
text.description2: At 27 meters in the south, you will find two canyons and lots of beautiful soft coral. You can even spot the rare guitarshark here.

text.description1: This dive takes place on a faru located on the south-east side of the island of Naainfaru. A faru describes a long reef. It is a fairly easy drift dive that takes you along a beautiful reef sloping down from around 5 meters at the top to 25 meters at the bottom.
text.description2: A great place to explore the many wonders hiding among the hard corals like octopus, turtles, and other reef dwellers. Watch for sleeping stingrays and eagle rays passing by.

text.description1: A nice and easy site 30 minutes to the south of Fairmont Maldives Sirru Fen Fushi. Located on the east of the local island Marosh, this dive site is usually done as a drift dive. The dive site features a very shallow top reef and a slope reaching to about 25 meters.
text.description2: We usually find many juvenile and young barracudas as well as turtles and schooling blue line snappers. Patches of leather coral and many anemones as well as sleeping nurse sting rays.

text.description1: This dive takes place on the reef on the north side of the island of Naainfaru. The reef slopes from 5 meters to 30 meters and features many overhangs. Overhangs are always a great spot to find soldierfish and macro life such as nudibranchs and shrimps.
text.description2: The top reef is home to several groups of humpback snappers and the beautiful yellow colored five line snappers. We often find turtles here, which feed on the corals and sponges.

text.description2: Shark lovers will find what they are looking for. Make sure you won’t miss out on tuna and big eye jackfish, as well as schooling fish on all sides of the thila.

text.description2: Check the overhangs for sleeping nurse sharks and rays. Sirru Thila is also a great place to watch grey reef sharks hunting in the current. A true Maldivian dive experience!

text.description2: Towards the west of the thila a school of humpback snappers can be found. Dogtooth tuna, Napoleon wrasses, and schooling fusiliers hunt in the current together with grey reef sharks.

Sirru Faru Dhekunu Kang is a spot for the experienced diver since its main attractions lie deep: Long overhangs at 25 to 30 meters. These overhangs are filled with beautiful gorgonians.
text.description2: Look out for sleeping nurse sharks and stingrays in the overhangs! In between the top reef at 5 meters to about 20 meters the reef features coral blocks.

text.description2: The top reef features an amazing hard coral garden. In the small overhangs and cracks in the reef formation you will spot the antennas of lobsters and curious moray eels peeking out.

text.description1: Sirru Faru Hulhangu is located about 15 minutes west of Fairmont Maldives Sirru Fen Fushi. As with most farus, it is a relatively easy drift dive along a beautiful coral covered reef. The top is at 5 meters and then slopes down to 30+ meters. At various depths you will find overhangs, some covered in beautiful soft corals.
text.description2: What to expect: Ghost pipefish, soft corals, marble stingrays, blacktip reef sharks as well as many other beautiful reef fish.

text.description1: THE CORALARIUM by JASON DECAIRES TAYLOR is a 100% sustainable Art installation which was completed in 2018. Under guidance of the Resident Marine Biologist Samuel Dixon a lot of additional shelter and valuable coral restoration projects were realized throughout the years to become the abundant reef it is now...
text.description2: In a depth from 2 to 6 meters a lot corals and fishes found a new home. Rare juvenile sweetlips, snappers, pipefishes as well as a tiny frogfish call this beautiful place their home...

text.description2: The dive site is a great spot to find turtles. The endangered hawksbill turtle is a very common inhabitant on this part of the reef.

text.description2: In between 12 meters and 25 meters, divers can admire the awe-inspiring view of various manta-cleaning stations during the north-east monsoon (December to April).

text.description2: Many garden eels and stingrays nap in the sand, often cleaned by cleaner wrasse. Look out for leaf fish hidden among the coral. Sometimes even mantas use this reef.

text.description1: Located in the inside of the atoll, currents tend to be minor. With the maximum depth being 20 meters, it is the perfect spot for all experience levels. The dive site is known for its amazing hard coral life, both on the thila and the main reef.
text.description2: You will be amazed at how many stingrays can be found at a single dive site. It is also home to the rare guitar ray and eagle rays. Sometimes even mantas are spotted on this reef.

text.description1: This site is on the east side of the local island of Feydhoo. A sloping reef starting at 5 meters and going down to around 30 meters offers an abundance of marine life as well as some nice overhangs on the north-east side of the reef.
text.description2: A great place to look for reef dwellers amongst the corals and rocks, such as lionfish, lobsters, and turtles. Out in the blue, a school of jackfish is never far away from the reef.

text.description1: This is a long channel dive site in the northeast corner of the atoll. Here you can expect strong currents as well as high seas when the weather is rough. A great spot for large fish species.
text.description2: In this channel, you can encounter large numbers of grey reef sharks and schools of silvertip sharks.

text.description1: Shallow top reef with interesting boulder and old coral formations, sloping to sand at an average of 20-25m. Deep overhangs and shelves close to the sandy bottom offering refuge and hiding places for lobsters, rays and grouper among others
text.description2: Soft corals, anemones, schooling fusilier and jacks, lobster, small reef sharks, various rays including eagle rays and occasional manta have been seen at this location.

text.description1: This long narrow “thila“ is made up of three separate pinnacles, starting from 30-35m and finishing with the shallowest part at 15m, this dive site is for those looking for a deeper dive. Best dived with nitrox.
text.description2: This is a great dive site to spot tuna and eagle rays, and sometimes even manta rays with the right conditions.

text.description1: Finey is one the most colourful thilas in the area. The top of thila is around 15 metres and drops to its base at around 30 metres. The entire thila wall is completely covered by yellow, blue, purple and orange soft corals. A small canyon at one end offers refuge to a vast array of species.
text.description2: Some hard, but mostly colourful soft corals, eagle rays, schooling fish, napoleon fish, sharks, tuna and a lot of reef life such as shrimps, lobsters and nudibranchs.

text.description1: Surrounded by open ocean. Suitable for advanced divers only. Two separated thilas, the highest point of the first thila is at around 14 metres and it drops to its base until 30 metres.
text.description2: The thila and surrounding rocks are covered by soft corals and it’s possible to see eagle rays, tuna fish, sharks and all sorts of reef fish.

text.description1: A typically shallow top reef, gently sloping to a sandy bottom at 25-30m. The slope is covered with many large rock formations, small ledges and overhangs, offering refuges to fish, turtles, morays and some macro subjects.
text.description2: Many hard, branching corals, some small fan corals and many schooling fusilier as well as snapper, turtles, tuna, boxfish, bluefin, giant trevally, whitetips and the usual reef dwellers

text.description1: A medium sized thila, the highest point being around 14 meters, dropping to its base at around 30 meters. Here we descend in open water, to the base, circling the thila a few times while shallowing, to discover many differences from bottom to top.
text.description2: Some soft corals, including some large fans, morays, octopus, turtles and whitetips can be seen here, along with various rays and all the usual reef fishes.

text.description1: This dive often begins on the shallower sandy patches, between the older coral formations within the natural, shallow lagoon. Moving to the edge, down and along the wall, eventually descending down to the sandy bottom at about 25 meters, where some large blocks of corals and rocks are full of life.
text.description2: Nurse sharks and stingrays resting. Schools of fusiliers and yellow snappers keep us company throughout the dive and turtles and octopus are often seen with all the usual reef dwellers.

text.description1: Small Thila dropping to 30m on the deepest side with a top at around 15m, located a short distance from the main faru (reef). Plenty of hard and soft corals with some overhangs on the deeper side, often patrolled by large jack fish, (blue fin and giant trevally), white tip reef sharks and sting rays on the sand
text.description2: The top is covered with the usual suspects, reef fish and the common species around the corals, including some morays and the odd octopus

text.description1: Suitable for all levels of experience. The dive starts in shallow waters with a sloping top reef, dropping down to the sandy seabed at 25 metres.
text.description2: Blue fusiliers, snappers, sea turtles, white tip sharks and in the right season (usually during the south west monsoon period) manta rays.

text.description1: This dive spot is on the north-eastern corner of Hanimaadhoo Island. Suitable for all levels of experience. The top reef sits around 5-7m and is covered with interesting boulder and coral formations, gently sloping off to a sandy bottom at an average depth of 20m.
text.description2: All the usual, colourful reef dwellers, rays, sharks, turtles and schooling fusiliers, jack fish and snappers. Smaller macro species can also be found here.

text.description1: Within sight of our resort jetty and bordering our beautiful lagoon, the Barefoot House Reef is the perfect dive site for entry level and experienced divers alike. This is a shallow top reef, gently sloping to a sandy bottom at around 12m, often with very little to no current. Suitable for all.
text.description2: The usual reef fish common to the Maldives, black tip, white tip & nurse sharks, sting rays, eagle rays, and even manta rays can be seen along with lobster, octopus, and macro species.

text.description1: A shallow house reef of Hondaafushi Island, starting at around 5 metres, sloping to beyond 18-20 metres in places. Some large boulders teeming with life on the top reef and slope with some small cave type overhangs, often hiding rays, whitetips and large groups of lobsters.
text.description2: Mostly hard corals with many schooling snappers and fusiliers, napoleon fish, whitetip reefsharks, turtles, rays and occasionally even manta rays have been spotted.

text.description1: Located on the east side of Hondaafushi Island. Suitable for all levels of divers. The dive takes place on a sandy plateau, among many coral blocks and the acropora and table coral families, before sloping down to a sandy bottom at around 15-20m.
text.description2: Schools of fusiliers, white tip sharks and stingrays. Turtles, napoleon fish, bat fish, snappers and all the usual reef dwellers.

text.description1: A large plateau like thila, in the channel between Baarah & Hanimaadhoo, this dive site has provided opportunities to see everything from mantis shrimp to manta rays and even sail fish circling above. A large rocky plateau, covered in older rock and coral formations, the top sits at 15m, dropping off at its sides to 30m.
text.description2: Everything from the typical reef dwellers, to macro species and large schools of fusiliers. Manta rays have been seen to frequent this thila, and sail fish have been sighted circling overhead.

text.description1: Reef wall from 8m to 25-30m with interesting boulder and old coral formations at the top to deep overhangs and caverns below, often with a changable current to watch for at times and cleaning stations spaced along the top reef, offering opportunities to spot manta rays and turtles in the right conditions/season.
text.description2: Soft corals and algae where turtles can be found feeding, large wrasse, grey reef sharks, eagle rays and schools of fusiler, snapper, jacks and batfish.

text.description1: Deep sheer wall to 25-30m from a top reef at around 7m. Deep caverns, overhangs, ledges and small caves at around 16m where white tips and nurse sharks can be seen along with rays resting. Macro life to be found in the deep caverns and along the wall / inside the small overhangs and openings.
text.description2: Stingrays, white tip sharks and lobsters in the small caves, schooling fusiliers and snappers over the top reef, dogtooth tunas, barracudas, eagle rays and turtles are all seen here.

text.description1: The dive begins on the top of the oceanic plateau at a depth of 8-12 metres, leading to a wall that slopes down to around 28 metres. There are many large coral blocks and small caves.
text.description2: Rich in residential reef fish, such as snapper, fusiliers, grouper, lobsters, morays and even turtles, green bump-head parrotfish, eagle rays, sharks and sometimes mantarays.

text.description1: This Divesite is located on the east side of the island Baarah and is covered in hardcoral. Easy to dive between 10 - 20m. Also good for beginners.
text.description2: Large schools of fish swimming between the coral blocks. Turtles are frequent visitors. There´s a group of Humphead Parrotfish living around the island Baarah.

text.description1: Starting on the shallow top reef at around 5 meters, sloping down to over 20 metres, we explore the reef and in the right conditions, out into the center of the channel to explore a small coral covered thila. Either way, this site offers lots of opportunities to explore many interesting coral and rock formations.
text.description2: Many turtles feed here and while the top reef bustles with the expected reef dwellers, eagle rays, mobula rays, sharks, eels and schooling fish are regularly sighted here.

text.description1: This can be a very easy dive in normal conditions, but also quite challenging in the case of strong currents. The reef starts in shallow waters and goes slowly down to 20 and to 30m in some areas. A large ’aquarium’ section is the highlight of this dive, along with small canyons and large overhangs full of soft corals.
text.description2: Blue soft corals in the overhangs and yellow soft corals adorn the rock at the aquarium. Schools of snappers, jacks, fusiliers, sharks, turtles, napoleon fish, bat fish and eagle rays.

text.description1: This divesite on the westside of the island Mulidhoo has lots of overhangs and caves that are waiting to be explored. Looking into the blue can be very rewarding too.
text.description2: Different kinds of stingrays and reefsharks sleeping in the caves. Look out into the blue... Eaglerays are frequent visitors of this divesite.

text.description1: Between the two islands Mafaahi and Muraido, near the canal to the port of Muraido, two long ridges can be found. Depth varies between 15m and 22m.
text.description2: The ridges are covered in hard coral. In the sandy bottom stingrays can be found. Turtles are frequent visitors and with a bit of luck you might spot some devil rays.

text.description1: The top reef at Utheemu starts shallow, with a slope/drop off reaching up to 25m+ at the sand. Often with a reasonable current, this site offers opportunities to explore some older coral and rock formations with frequent sightings of grey reef, nurse sharks and eagle rays.
text.description2: All the common reef dwellers can be found here around the many boulders and outcrops. Rays, sharks, schooling fusilier, snapper and jacks are common, as well as some macro subjects.

text.description1: This dive site is a pinnacle on the west side of Filladhoo Island. Suitable for all levels of dive experience. There are some nice overhangs along the pinnacle wall.
text.description2: This site offers varied fish sightings like blue trigger fish, groupers, Napoleon wrasse, as well as schools of snapper. Sometimes manta rays can be spotted here.

text.description1: This dive is located on the south reef of Takandhoo Island. Suitable for all levels of experience. We start in shallow water on the top reef, heading deeper on the slope to some small caves / openings, ending at the corner of the reef around some interesting rock formations, between 18 and 30 metres deep.
text.description2: Sting rays, snappers, groupers and fusiliers. Blue trigger fish and sometimes out in the blue you can spot eagle rays and tuna.

text.description1: A beautiful channel location, with a very shallow top reef, sloping to sand at 18-25m, covered with hard and soft corals, abundant with marine life, often with a slight to medium current.
text.description2: Schooling jacks, snappers, fusiliers, mobula rays, eagle rays and sting rays, plus the occasional manta, along with many reef dwelling species from sharks to mantis shrimp and nudi’s.

text.description1: Starting on a beautiful top reef at just 5 meters deep, progressing to a drop off and wall that reaches depths of 30 meters. Along the reef wall there are some large overhangs, where it is possible to see sleeping sting rays or turtles, lion fish, moray eels and lobsters.
text.description2: Eagle rays, sharks, Napoleonfish and barracuda can pass us by, while friendly schools of bat fish have been known to follow us while we dive.

text.description1: Aquarium is a dive site located at Mulidhoo Island. It is suitable for all levels of experience. The dive site has a drop off which gives way to a sloping reef dropping down to 25 meters.
text.description2: Manta Rays on the cleaning stations. Grey reef sharks, with occasional eagle ray sightings and napoleon fish. Aquarium offers great subjects for photos and videos.

text.description1: Depending on the current, either we dive the wall or the caves from the same spot. Suitable for most levels. The top reef sits at around 6 metres, sloping to a wall that drops to around 30. Most of the dive is spent under the large overhangs where the main wall and ceilings are covered by yellow, soft corals.
text.description2: Tuna, eagle rays, reef sharks and occasionally manta out in the blue. The common reef species like parrot fish, groupers, all the schooling fish and sometimes turtles are often spotted.

text.description1: A deep wall dive, starting on a top reef with many hard corals, descending over the edge and down a shear wall, covered in yellow, soft corals to eventual deep overhangs / caverns at its base, around 30m depth.
text.description2: Many hard and soft corals covering the top reef and reef wall. Schooling fusiliers and jack fish, eagle rays, turtles and occasionally manta rays.

text.description1: A shallow 10m top reef, sloping to a beautiful reef wall, dropping to 30m, covered in soft and hard corals, with one large, colourful, naturally formed arch.
text.description2: Hard, soft corals, eagle rays, tunas, groupers, snappers, fusiliers and nurse sharks, sting rays and even dolphins and manta have been seen here.

text.description1: The Filladhoo wreck is the northern-most wreck site in the Maldives, located in Haa Dhaalu Atoll. You will find it to the south of Filladhoo Island and parts of the wreck are breaking the water’s surface.
text.description2: This site is a great refuge for large green sea turtles and schools of eagle rays as well as many small tropical fish.

text.description1: This site is situated close to Dhidhdhoo Island and a naturally formed sandbank. Suitable for most divers. The dive starts on the top reef at a depth of 10 to 12 meters, sloping to 25 to 30 meters at the base.
text.description2: Very good for grey reef sharks and tuna, snappers, jack fish and barracuda. Here you can also see stingrays, eagle rays, and mantas passing by or circling the many cleaning stations.

text.description1: This channel located in the north of Southern Huvadhoo Atoll is perfect for drift diving and current lovers. Depending on the direction of the current, you will either start your dive to the north of the channel or the south and just go with the flow.
text.description2: The south of Maldives is well known for its pelagics. This dive site doesn’t disappoint with common sightings of grey reef sharks, leopard sharks, and silvertip sharks.

text.description1: A beautiful wall dive, covered with corals at all levels, the dive begins on the top reef at a depth of 10 to 12 meters, following the wall down to a slope at around 18 meters, before dropping further to around 30 metres, where we can explore some large sequential overhangs and caverns at the base.
text.description2: Hard and soft corals cover this wall at all levels. Sharks, schooling fusiliers, bat fish, snappers, mantis shrimp, octopus, lobster and many rays often to be seen here.

text.description1: This channel dive site, located to the east of the atoll, is a protected area where fishing has been banned. Due to this you can encounter sharks in large numbers.
text.description2: Upon reaching the right spot in the channel and with the right currents, you can enjoy a dive with over 100 grey reef sharks here as well as schooling silver tip sharks.

text.description1: This dive site is for advanced divers who are comfortable diving in the blue water with no reference other than your dive instruments and diving buddy.
text.description2: This special blue water site plays host to hammerhead sharks as well as silky sharks. With the ocean there is no guarantee, but this is a good spot to try your luck!
